ic very similar to oceanic versus continental now oceanic versus oceanic the denser colder older crust is going to subduct underneath the other and it's adding water as it subducts which is going to lower the melting point and it's going to promote partial melting at a certain depth because of the pressures and temperatures and the water added promote that melting that melted material is going to form magma that magma is going to rise to the surface and it's going to form a volcano now this is oceanic versus oceanic so the volcanoes are not going to be on a continent but they will be on the sea floor and if these volcanoes get large enough they will pop out of the water and they will form islands like japan or the lucian islands but they're not considered continental crust material they're oceanic crust materials just so much crust material that it's actually above the water creating these island arcs now just like with oceanic versus continental boundary we get those explosive volcanoes now because as the magma rises it also melts stuff along the way and it can melt i don't know if you can see here the sediments that are sitting on the sea floor these sediments even though it's on oceanic crust the sediments came from a continent so they're made up of continental material they have silica remember i said silica makes magma lava very sticky and very explosive so these volcanoes can also be explosive in nature now we also get those mega thrust earthquakes because anytime we have subduction going on it's not a smooth process it gets stuck sometimes and when it gets stuck it's going to get unstuck at some point and it's going to form that earthquake and of course we're definitely underwater here when that happens it's going to displace water and it's going to form a tsunami so at these zones we also have explosive volcanoes we also have large magnitude earthquakes just like the 2011 tohoku earthquake that we talked about and tsunami just like in japan so these are also