oto shows a really great example of that here we have a dry creek channel here on to the south of the san andreas fault it's moving north but look what happens as it reaches the san andreas fault it's displaced and moved shortly to the east where it continues on north up here and these transform faults not only can displace rivers they can displace mountain chains and they can even displace things that we make like roads and fence lines things like that can be displaced slowly over time so it's really important to pay attention whenever you're choosing a place to live or building a structure to make sure you're not building anything on top of a transform plate boundary because they are moving and they will continue to move all right so a little summary about transform boundaries transform boundaries are a tectonic boundary where two tectonic plates slide past one another again no crust is being created and no crust is being destroyed here we are just sliding past one another they occur most commonly along segments of the mid-ocean ridge and if you look on google earth along all of the mid-ocean ridges in the atlantic the pacific and the indian you'll see that they're heavily fractured and displaced and those fractures are transformed faults or transform plate boundaries but we do have some transformed faults that occur on continental crust the most famous example is that san andreas fault zone in southern california now hazards here include earthquakes but there are no volcanoes associated with these type of boundaries now although earth's total surface area does not change the size and shape of individual plates are constantly changing because plate boundaries are changing through time they migrate some plate boundaries end up getting created whenever we start having that rifting happening like what's happening in east africa we're going to eventually create a new ocean creating new plate boundaries and plate boundaries can be destroyed eventually you could have th