howdy again everyone we are going to continue on in module 2 talking about the testing the model of plate tectonics with ocean drilling and paleomagnetism so you're probably aware that the earth has a magnetic field and this magnetic field has invisible lines of force that pass through the planet and extend from one magnetic pole to the other out into space creating the shield around the earth that we know as the magnetosphere today the magnetic poles are roughly aligned with the geographic poles where the earth's rotational axis intersects the surface earth's magnetic field is a little less obvious to us than the gravitational field and that's because we can't feel the magnetic field however the movement of a compass needle confirms its presence a traditional compass needle is usually just a small magnet that's free to rotate on an axis and it becomes aligned with those magnetic lines of force when it's laid flat one end of the compass will point to magnetic north while the other end of the compass points to magnetic south now the magnetic poles can move over time though but they usually stay in the vicinity of the north and south geographic poles here is a map that shows how the magnetic poles have moved over human time scales and let me get my laser pointer going this red line represents the motion of that magnetic pull through time you can think of it as where the bar magnet is intercepting the surface so it does slightly move over time but for the most part it's staying within the vicinity of the geographic pool now earth's magnetic field has two main components we call it declination and inclination declination is the difference between where magnetic north is and the geographic true north and inclination is the tilt of a compass needle from the horizontal the geographic north is the center of rotation again remember it's where that rotational axis intersects the surface of the earth that's what we consider the geographic north and that's usually different than the true magnetic north however they are in close vicinity of each other that declination is going to be the difference between those two and that can change over time and the compass is pointing to magnetic north it does not point to the true geographic north so when you have your compass it is pointing to where that bar magnet you can think of within the earth is actually pointing to now some naturally occurring minerals are magnetic and those minerals can be influenced by earth's magnetic field one of the most common is the iron rich mineral called magnetite which is abundant in lava flows of basaltic composition remember our oceanic crust is predominantly basalt in nature so we have a ton of this iron-rich minerals located in the oceanic crust now basaltic lavas erupt at surface temperatures greater than 1800 degrees fahrenheit which exceed a threshold temperature for magnetism which is known as the curie point now the magnetite grains and the molten lava are non-magnetic but as the lava cools these iron-rich grains become magnetized and they then align themselves in the direction of the existing magnetic lines of force just like a compass needle once the mineral solidifies though that magnetism usually remains somewhat frozen in place and it preserves the position of earth's magnetic field at the time it crystallized so these rocks that form thousands or even sometimes millions of years ago may actually contain a record of the direction of the magnetic poles at the time of their formation and they're able to tell us the latitude and the longitude in which the rock first formed this study of fossil magnetism to understand the earth's history is called paleomagnetism now studies of paleomagnetism revealed that during the past 500 million years the magnetic pole had gradually wandered from its location from near hawaii northeastward to its present location over the arctic ocean that's pretty strange this was strong evidence that either the magnetic north pole had migrated an idea known as polar wandering or that the poles had remained roughly in place and it was the continents that had drifted beneath them if you just look at that magnetic alignment of the iron-rich minerals in the lava flows which is shown here in this figure it would indicate that the paleomagnetic folds change dramatically through time take a look at that even though the magnetic pool is known to move like we just saw a few slides ago the positions of the magnetic full still correspond pretty closely to the geographic poles therefore the most acceptable explanation was already provided by good old wegner's hypothesis of continental drift further evidence for continental drift came shortly after this discovery when polar wandering path was constructed for north america as seen here for the first 200 million years or so the paths for north america and europe were found to be in similar direction but they are separated by about 3 000 miles then during the middle of the mesozoic era which was about 180 million years ago they began to converge on to the present north pole the explanation for these curves is that north america and europe were joined at one point until the mesozoic and that's when the atlantic began to open and pangaea began to break apart now some of the most convincing evidence for sea floor spreading actually came from the deep sea drilling project which operated from 1966 to 1983. one of the early goals of the project was to gather samples of the ocean floor to establish its age using a drilling ship that was capable of working in thousands of meters deep of water they drilled hundreds of holes through layers of sediment that covered the oceanic crust and they even were able to drill well into the basaltic rock below now these researchers were then able to record the age of the sediment samples from each site that they drilled and they noted each sample's distance away from that mid-ocean ridge and they found that the sediments increased in age with an increase in distance from the ridge this of course supported harry hess and a sea floor spreading hypothesis now the deep sea drilling project was crucial in understanding our planet and the geologic processes that we know now today exist but did you know that it has a long continued history and is even located on campus today the deep sea drilling project ended in 1983 but then it became known as the ocean drilling program or odp and that existed from 1983 to 2003. then in 2003 it became the integrated ocean drilling program until 2013 when it became what we now know it as today as the international ocean discovery program this wonderful organization is actually located here on our campus and it has tons of cores and samples from various projects over the past several decades i have even been using their data on my research on underwater landslides i highly recommend if you ever get a chance to check this facility out now oceanographers also began running their own surveys of the ocean floor during their efforts to make detailed maps of the sea floor topography or sometimes we just call it the symmetry these surveys were accomplished by towing very sensitive instruments called magnetometers magnetometers that measured the strength of the earth's magnetic field recorded in the rocks below it these oceanographers found that the magnetism varied perpendicular to the mid-ocean ridges and that anomalies existed in linear belts parallel to the ridges shown here this relatively simple pattern of magnetic variation you could see the pattern the colors repeat on either side of the ridge further supported the concept of that c4 spreading the stripes of high intensity magnetism are regions where the paleomagnetism of the ocean crust exhibits normal clarity and the low intensity strips are regions where the ocean crust is polarized in the reverse direction this brings us to our next topic of magnetic pole reversals geophysicists discovered that over periods of hundred or thousands of years earth's magnetic field periodically reversed polarity normal polarity is when the north geographic pole and the north magnetic pool coincide like today reverse polarity is when the north geographic pool and the south magnetic pole coincide you can kind of think of it as the bar magnet being flipped upside down inside the earth now how do how do these parallel strips that oceanographers discover become distributed across the ocean floor well remember as the lava magma solidify at the crest of the ridge it is magnetized with the polarity of the earth's magnetic field at the time it was formed because of sea floor spreading this strip of magnetized crust would gradually increase in width until of course the next reversal takes place and here's a cool graphic that illustrates that exact process your textbook also goes into more detail to help better explain this super interesting topic but in our next video we're going to explore testing the model

