howdy everyone and welcome to the last video of module two now this video is going to be a short one even though we're describing what drives plate motion so you think that it would be a fairly long video however as you'll soon learn geologists still don't quite agree on what exactly the the driving motion of our planet is being caused by but we'll explore some models so what drives the plates motions geologists have discovered that the lithospheric plates are part of the larger convection system that produces the plate motion now convection is the way heat transfers through liquids and gases it quite simply implies that hot things will rise while cool things will sink now convection works because cold material is denser than the same material when it's heated up this earth's internal convection which is a little more complex than just a pot of boiling water has two main forces that are driving the plate motion we have a slab pole and ridge push geologists agree that the subduction of cold dense slabs of oceanic lithosphere is the major driving force of plate motion slab pole occurs because these cold slabs of oceanic lithosphere is denser than the underlying warm asthenosphere and they sink kind of like a ship's anchor would sink when you throw it out into the water the slabs are being pulled down by the mantle or into the mantle by gravity now another important driving force however not as significant as slab pool is ridge push and this occurs along mid-ocean ridges at mid-ocean ridges this is where we have that newly formed oceanic lithosphere that's being pushed away and this gravity-driven mechanism that's what we call the ridge push and it's resulted from the elevated position of the oceanic ridges which causes those new slabs of lithosphere to kind of slide down both flanks of the rich just like how gravity pulls down snow during an avalanche now here's a figure showing both of those driving forces in action and again let me get my little laser pointer so here we have slab pole being illustrated slab pull results from that sinking of the cold dense slab of oceanic lithosphere and this is the major driving force of plate motion because gravity just like an anchor when you throw it overboard is gonna gravity's gonna sink it and it's gonna sink it pretty fast as it moves down so that's what's pulling the plates that slab pole again that's the major driving force over here we have ridge push being illustrated and ridge push is a gravity driven force that results from just the elevated position of the ridge so we have new lithosphere being formed right here and it's hot so it's it's elevated and gravity is going to cause it to sink down as it's being pushed away so we have a little bit of a pushing motion happening at those mid-ocean ridges but the main force is that pull that's going on at that subduction zone although not fully understood researchers agree that plate tectonics and convection flow in the mantle are part of the same system now remember plate tectonics is still a relatively new theory it wasn't established until the 1960s which if you think about it your parents may have been alive then or definitely your grandparents weren't so we are still learning more about these processes today now plate tectonics and convection flow in the mantle are part of that same system remember we have that slab pole in the ridge push and we agree that the energy source for plate tectonics is earth's internal heat so as a result many models have been proposed although we're going to examine just one type so in this model the whole mantle model which is often referred to as the plume model you can see here that there are sinking slabs of cold oceanic lithosphere and it coincides with the downward limbs or those downward yellow arrows that you see of the convection cells while you can also see that rising mantle plumes right here are carrying hot material from that core mantle boundary towards the earth's surface so this also helps 