ke a mcdonald's milkshake contains minerals who knew things like makeup and eye shadow hard rubber materials and cell phone and car batteries all rely on minerals nearly everything we use comes from minerals in some way or another all right so what exactly is a mineral in the first place well minerals are the building blocks of rocks and a mineral has a definition with five characteristics in order to be classified as a mineral it must be naturally occurring it must be generally inorganic so nothing organic is going to be considered a mineral and a mineral must have an orderly crystalline structure and be solid so no liquids no gases and finally a mineral has to have a definite chemical composition that could allow for some variation what do i mean by chemical composition i mean that every mineral has its own chemical formula for example a very common mineral on earth's crust called quartz has a chemical formula of sio2 that means there's one silica atom bonded to two oxygen atoms and then minerals are the building blocks of rocks and we kind of talked about rocks in the first module where a rock is a solid mass of minerals or mineral-like matter that occurs naturally and of course the earth is made up of rocks and rocks are made up of minerals so it's important that we spend some time or at least a module in talking about these minerals because they make up our entire earth so if minerals makes rocks what makes minerals atoms atoms are the building blocks of minerals and atoms are the smallest particles of matter that cannot be chemically split they are composed of a nucleus that contains protons which are positively charged and neutrons which are neutral or have no electrical charge and this nucleus is surrounded by electrons which have a negative charge now all of this might be review because you've probably taken chemistry in high school or maybe another class on campus so i'm just going to briefly reintroduce a little bit of chemistry because it's important to understand how atoms work in order to understand how minerals are made and then of course rocks in the rest of the earth but i highly recommend that you read your textbook especially on these sections if you need a more in-depth review now electrons exist as a cloud of negative charges that surround the nucleus that has the positively charged protons in the neutral neutrons and these electrons are moving about the nucleus in regions called principal shells and the outermost shell contains something that we call valence electrons and these valence electrons are interacting with other atoms to form chemical bonds now there are many different models of an atom we have the easy to understand or easier to understand models of the spatial shell model that have electrons that are fixed on a spherical surface around the nucleus and we have the planetary orbit model that have electrons orbiting around the nucleus and then we have more complex models like the electroneum model and the probability models which are interpretations of the solutions of the schrodinger's equation as wave functions and eigen energies now don't worry you don't need to know all that but what you should know is that the probability model is the most accurate model of an atom and that's because the atomic orbital is shown as a region with an atom that encloses and that's where the electron is likely to be 90 of the time because in reality electrons are not orbiting nicely like you see in the spatial shell in the planetary orbit model rather these electrons are very chaotic and bounce around in a non-predictable way and that's why our probability model is the most accurate model that we know of of the atom now when we talk about atoms we should talk about what an atomic number is because i'm going to show you here soon the periodic table of elements and if you remember from chemistry class elements have an atomic number the atomic number is the number of protons in the nucleus of an atom and it determines the atom's chemical nature and it's important to remember that that the atom determines the atomic chemical nature the number of protons all right so i am going to introduce the table of elements here soon so what is an element an element is a group of the same kind of atoms and approximately there are 90 natural elements and then there are several others that have been synthesized in a laboratory now these elements are organized in the periodic table which again i'm going to show here shortly and they're organized in this table so that those with similar properties line up into groups and it's really useful so there's a reason this table has the funky shape it has now most elements join with other elements to form chemical compounds an example of a chemical compound would be something as simple as table salt which is made up of a mineral called halite halite is sodium and chloride bonded together that's a chemical compound nacl sodium chloride all right so here's that periodic table of elements now here in the periodic table of elements you could see that each element has a number and the number on top that's the atomic number remember the atomic number tell us how many protons are in that atom so let's just use carbon as an example do you see carbon carbon has number six it's on the right hand side of the periodic table now carbon's atomic number is six that means it has six protons now let's talk about noble gases noble gases can easily be found on the periodic table it is the last column on the right hand side noble gases are inert that means they are chemically inactive and that is because their outer shell is full of electrons so they tend to not have a tendency to want to gain or lose those electrons because they're already stable now all the rest of the elements are considered unstable and they're ready to react and that is because their outer shell is not full of electrons at least not yet they have room to gain or lose electrons in most atoms they want to become stable like those noble gases they want their outer shell to be full so in order to achieve this they will lose or gain electrons now a general rule of thumb is that most atoms want to be surrounded by eight valence electrons to be considered full so the periodic table has roman numerals above each column and these roman numerals represent the number of valence electrons that particular column of elements have for example elements in the first column you'll see has the roman numeral one see how it has one a above that first column this means that the elements in this column have one valence electron so those elements are more likely to lose that one electron than they are to gain seven electrons and the second column elements has the roman numeral two above it and these elements have two valence electrons so those elements are more likely to lose two electrons than they are to gain six more so all the elements on the left side of the table have a tendency to lose electrons now again if you notice the noble gases the noble gases have a roman numeral eight above their column that is because they already have eight electrons in their outer shell which makes them stable which makes them inert the column to the left of the noble gases has a roman numeral 7 above it this means these elements have 7 valence electrons so they are more likely to gain one electron than they are to lose all seven the next one to the left of that has a roman numeral six this means these elements have six valence electrons so they are more likely to gain two electrons than they are to lose those six electrons so the elements on the right side of the table have a tendency to gain electrons under normal conditions found on earth most elements form bonds with atoms of other elements with the exception of those noble gases that do not like to bond because they are already stable a chemical bond is a transfer or sharing of electrons that allows each atom to attain a full valence shell of electrons remember valence is just a fancy word for the outer shell some atoms bond to form ionic compounds some form molecules and some form metallic substances here is another useful way to imagine the valence shell of an atom remember the octet rule in most atoms want eight electrons so you can see the column seven like the element chlorine see where the roman numeral seven is the second column to the left chlorine is represented by cl if you take a look at that element chlorine it is only missing one electron to be considered full so this element would be most likely to bond to an element with one electron because it needs one electron now an element that has one electron is sodium which is in that first column underneath roman numeral one and sodium is represented by n a you see n a has one electron so this sodium is more than happy to get rid of its electron to the chlorine to become more stable this process is a type of bonding called ionic bonding to produce a solid ionic compound of sodium chloride which again is that mineral called halite or you probably know it better as table salt now in ionic bonding atoms gain or lose outermost valence electrons to form ions and ions are just positively or negatively charged atoms it is an atom that has gained or lost one or more electrons ionic compounds consist of an orderly arrangement of oppositely charged ions so an ionic bond is the attraction of oppositely charged ions to one another again an example would be halite the table salt sodium chloride so here is a better illustration showing how that ionic bonding is working in halite remember halite is sodium chloride one sodium atom bonded to one chlorine atom you see here sodium has 11 protons and if we went back to the table of elements you would see that sodium has an atomic number of 11 so it has 11 protons and it also has 11 electrons and it gives away an electron to the chlorine so then it becomes positively charged because it still has 11 protons but now it only has 10 electrons so it has a plus 1 charge now chlorine has 17 protons because its atomic number is 17. and it also has 17 electrons it is given an electron from the sodium so it becomes negatively charged because now it has 18 electrons but still only has 17 protons giving it a negative one charge now both of these atoms have opposite charges so they are electrostatically attracted to each other creating that ionic bond now covalent bonds are much stronger than the ionic bonds covalent bonds are when a pair of atoms share one or more valence electrons between them instead of gaining or losing it completely a great example of this is the hydrogen molecule which is made up of two hydrogen atoms here you can see the two hydrogen atoms combined to form a hydrogen molecule hydrogen is one of those exceptions of the octet rule because it only contains a single shell which becomes full with only two electrons instead of eight so imagine two hydrogen atoms which each contain one proton and one electron approaching each other once they meet the electron configuration changes so that both electrons primarily occupy the space between the atoms in other words the two electrons are shared by both hydrogen atoms in this situation they do not form ions instead these forces that hold the atoms together arises from the attraction of oppositely charged particles the positively charged protons in the nuclei and the negatively charged electrons that surround it so what is the difference between ionic and covalent bonds again remember ionic bonds are electrostatically attracted while covalent bonds are sharing electrons now a few minerals such as native gold silver and copper are made entirely of metal atoms packed tightly together in an orderly way the bonding that holds these atoms together results from each atom contributing its valence electrons to a common pole of electrons which are free to move throughout the entire metallic structure this is why metals have high electrical conductivity and it's why they tend to be malleable and ductile while ionic and covalent bonded minerals are more brittle to visualize this difference picture dropping a ceramic plate on the floor versus dropping a metal spoon on the floor again how do electrons behave in a mineral with metallic bonding the electrons move relatively easily from atom to atom then we also have hybrid bonds that exhibit some degree of electron sharing and some degree of electron transfer silicate minerals which we will talk about later are composed of these hybrid bonds now here's a figure showing that metallic bonding a little bit easier you can see here the central core of each metallic atom has an overall positive charge and consists of the nucleus and inner electrons however within this structure there is a c you can think of it as of negatively charged outer electrons and there are free to move throughout the entire structure and surround those positive ions again this is what makes it have a high electrical conductivity and makes metals very malleable all right so that's our review on chemistry we are now going to move into more on what makes a mineral a mineral and the different properties of a mineral however if you're still a little confused about the chemistry i highly recommend that you review those sections in your textbook

