it more streak is the color of a powdered mineral so when we pulverize the mineral into a powder the color of that powder is actually much more useful than the outward appearance of that mineral now the powdered mineral will always be the same regardless of the outward color appearance here i have my favorite example on the left you see a silver shiny mineral this is called hematite and on the right you see a very dull earthy red mineral this is also hematite look at these two mineral samples they're the same exact mineral but they look completely different and that's why we can't rely on the outward color of a mineral to define it however in the center of this image i have a streak plate which is usually a ceramic plate and if you take the lab portion of this class you're going to experiment with this but if i polarize the mineral onto the streak plate and observe the color of the powder that's left behind you will notice that they both have a reddish brown streak regardless of which sample i pulverized again this is why streak is a much more useful property to identify a mineral all right hardness is a really great property that we use and hardness is the resistance of a mineral to scratching and geologists use something called the most scale of hardness which i have pictured here now this is just a relative scale between the values of 1 and 10. there is no equation that you can plug numbers into to actually calculate this kind of a value again this is just a relative scale what do i mean by relative scale i mean that we assign values to this scale so a value of one is assigned to the softest mineral we know which is talc powder is made of talc it's very soft that gets a value of 1. now we assign a value of 10 to the hardest mineral that we know about which is diamond diamond is the hardest mineral on earth that gets a value of 10. so anything in between 1 and 10 just means it's harder than baby powder but it's softer than a diamond now hardness is determined by the strength of the bonds holding the atoms together so the stronger the atomic bonds the harder the mineral is going to be so the hardness is actually a really useful property that's directly related to the atomic strength so why are diamonds so hard in the first place here we're going to explore what exactly makes diamonds so hard well remember the last video we went over when we talked about the different types of atomic bonds diamonds are made up of covalent bonds and if you look at the chemical formula of diamond you'll see that it's just made up of carbon c pretty easy to remember but these carbon atoms are covalently bonded to each other remember covalent bonds is when atoms share electrons to make themselves more stable and strong so here you can see the internal structure of diamond if you were an engineer you'd say this structure looks very stable that's because these carbon atoms are sharing electrons and arranging themselves in a very stable orderly three-dimensional structure which makes diamond very strong so let's look at graphite next if you'll notice graphite's chemical formula is also c carbon graphite and diamond are made up of the same exact material they both are made up of carbon but there are two completely different minerals graphite has the same exact composition as diamond but it is very different because it's very very soft if you didn't know graphite is what makes pencil lead what do we do with pencil lead we smear it on the paper graphite is so soft that it will break off a long paper but it's made up of the same stuff as diamonds which is the hardest material known to man why in the world are they very different well that's because of the atomic bonds here's a structure of graphite you'll see that the carbon atoms are bonded together in sheets and these sheets are held together by something called van der waals bonds which we didn't really talk about but van der waals bonds are weak electrical forces that attract neutral molecules to one another so it is a much weaker bond than our covalent bonds van der waals bonds are kind of similar to ionic bonds where it's an electrostatic attraction that's keeping them together so it's much easier to peel these sheets of carbon from each other because they're not sharing electrons like the diamond is now diamonds and graphites are something called polymorphs polymorphs are minerals with identical composition but different crystalline structures thus making them different minerals altogether all right now another property of minerals is something called cleavage and fracture now cleavage and fractured they both describe how a mineral breaks now these are kind of different difficult concepts to understand especially in a lecture kind of format it is much easier to understand these in lab so if you take the lab portion of this class you are going to explore these properties in much greater detail now cleavage is the tendency of a mineral to break in preferred directions along planar surfaces and it's determined by the varying strength of bonds within the mineral a mineral with cleavage will always break where the bonds are weakest so minerals with cleavage are predictable and repeatable as they break no matter the scale now a fracture is the tendency of a mineral to break along random irregular surfaces these minerals that do not have cleavage will not break in a predictable repeatable fashion because there is no specific planes of weakness in its internal atomic structure well that's a lot of confusing words right well cleavage and fracture both describe how a mineral breaks when we have cleavage we can predict how the mineral will break because we know in that mineral there are varying strengths of bonds and a mineral will always break where the bond is weakest now with fracture when we break these minerals we can't predict how they're going to break because all of the atomic bonds are relatively the same strength so it's unpredictable on how it's going to break it's going to break very randomly a great example of this is if i took a glass vase and i threw it on the ground in front of you other than being completely terrified you wouldn't be able to predict the sizes and shape that that glass vase is going to break into right but if i was to take a big chunk of salt and throw it on the ground i can predict how that's going to break that's because salt has cleavage it is always going to break into little cubes no matter how small salt breaks it'll always break into little cubes i don't know if you've ever held salt underneath a magnifying glass but you'll see that they are indeed tiny little cubes and that's because salt the atomic bonds within that mineral there is a weak plane there's actually three weak planes that causes it to be acute whereas in glass all of the atomic bonds are relatively the same strength and it's just going to break very randomly so here's an example of cleavage again this is called mica or biotite micas are bonded together in sheets that are kind of electrostatically attracted to each other they're ionic bonds ionic bonds are easier to break so with this type of mineral the weakest plane is going to be in between these sheets you can peel this mineral off literally like paper and i think you actually get to play with this mineral in lab if you take the lab portion of this course but this is an example of having one plane of cleavage example a is showing another example of one plane of cleavage but you can also have minerals that have two planes where there are two planes of weaknesses in the atomic bonds or three planes like salt as an example where it breaks off into cubes because there are three planes of weaknesses in that atomic strength and here's some photos just showing fracture on the left we have concoidal fracture where this mineral is breaking very randomly but in a concaved kind of pattern the mineral on the right is very irregular again we cannot predict how either of these minerals are going to break because all of the atomic bonds within these minerals are relatively the same strength we don't have a weak repeated layer all right luster is another property that geologists use and luster describes the way a mineral reflects off of light now there are many different terms that we use for luster quite simply you can have non-metallic versus metallic which means does the mineral reflect light like a metal or not like a metal an example of metallic would be something on the far right called pyrite now when we're talking about non-metallic minerals there are many different ways that light can be reflected off of its surface we have a silky kind of luster like on the left serpentine we have glassy which is there in the center but we have many different terms that we can describe the way a mineral reflects light we can even have opaque where mineral does not travel through it now if you take the lab portion of this class you're going to explore this property in a much more greater detail but for the purpose of this lecture portion all you need to know is that luster is just the way a mineral reflects light alright here's a really big one guys crystal form crystal form describes the geometric arrangement of crystal faces now when a mineral is free to grow in an unrestricted environment where it doesn't need to compete for space it obtains this beautiful crystal form in the shape of the crystal form is actually reflected in the internal structure of the crystal lattice so how those atoms are bonded together is reflected in the macroscopic form here with the shape of the crystal really cool stuff so why does quartz which i have shown here why does it have that pyramid shape well it is a direct result from the orderly atomic structure it has now specific gravity is another property that we use and in practice we really only use specific gravity to separate heavy minerals which are usually our metallic minerals from light minerals and specific gravity is really just the ratio of a mineral's weight in air to its weight in water so it's a unitless number now the higher the specific gravity the denser that mineral actually is so galena 7.2 is a lot denser than sulfur which would be a 2.1 and really what geologists do with this property is when they're out in the field they're picking up minerals and they're hefting it in their hand and saying oh this feels like a high specific gravity or ah this doesn't feel like a high specific gravity so really just in practice we use it to separate metals from nonmetals all right well there are a ton of other special properties that we could get into some minerals have a funky smell which i have shown here in the top left that yellow mineral sulfur sulfur smells like rotten eggs and below that we have this mineral called magnetite which is magnetic which is an also really cool property you can use to identify something so geologists out in the field sometimes carry magnets with them just to see what rocks end up being magnetic now in the top right i have shown calcite next to a bottle of hydrochloric acid now some minerals like carbonates will react to acid so some geologists will even keep this acid in their pocket and pull it out and pour acid on rocks while they're on a hike to see what reacts and what doesn't that's because calcite is actually quite a common rock for being a non-silicate it's one of the most common non-silicate minerals in our crust and it reacts to acid so it's an easy test to identify it and then on the bottom right there i have shown our halite our wonderful table salt guess what special property table salt has it tastes like salt so some crazy geologists will go on a hike and start licking rocks trying to find this stuff you think i'm kidding but i'm really not so here i have calcite shown again and i just think it's important because it is the most common non-silicate mineral and it does react with hydrochloric acid so it is an easy test to identify it now if you take the lab portion of this class you're probably going to play with hydrochloric acid and identify calcite yourself all right so here i just have shown a couple of minerals i have quartz olivine fluorite calcite and they can all occur in these beautiful crystalline forms here's a couple more native elements that are minerals like copper and gold yes they are both considered minerals again there are over 4 000 minerals but only about 20 of them are common in rocks now with this nearly 4000 minerals we can start categorize them into mineral groups now we have rock forming minerals and we have economic minerals there are only a few dozen of rock forming minerals and the common minerals that make up most of the rocks are found in the earth's crust and these are composed mainly of the eight elements that make up most of the continental crust and i'll show you that here in a moment whereas economic minerals are much less abundant these minerals are used extensively in manufacturing of products though now they're not always mutually exclusive groups for example calcite is an economic mineral and a rock forming mineral so here are the eight most abundant elements in the continental crust the eight elements that make up the vast majority of the rock foreign minerals represent more than 98 of the continental crust by weight and they are oxygen which is almost half silicon iron potassium magnesium sodium calcium and aluminum those are our eight most abundant elements in the continental crust now when we classify minerals we have a collection of specimens that exhibit similar internal structure and chemical composition and we call those mineral species we can even further divide mineral species up into mineral varieties for example there are many varieties of quartz we have smoky quartz which contain trace amounts of aluminum giving it its smoky color and we have amethyst which contains trace amount of iron giving it its color now mineral species are assigned to specific mineral groups and there are technically nine mineral groups but silicates carbonates halides sulfates those are all different mineral classes so here are the different mineral groups we have silicate minerals which are the most abundant of all naturally occurring inorganic compounds and then we have oxides sulfides carbonates sulfates halides and native elements you don't need to memorize all of this right now but for the purpose of this class we're just going to separate everything into two groups silicate versus non-silicate minerals again our silicate minerals are the most common type of minerals there are more than 800 known silicates and they account for more than 90 of the earth's crust silicon and oxygen is what makes up the basic building blocks of silicate minerals now non-silicate minerals are not as common as the silicate and they only make up about eight percent of the earth's crust now non-silicate minerals are still important economically and they include carbonates sulfates and halides and we're going to have two separate videos on silicate and non-silicate minerals later on in this module but our next video we're going to talk about how minerals are formed and the different ways we can destroy them

