howdy everyone and welcome to the continuation of module 3. in this video we're going to be talking about how minerals form and what are some of the ways that we can destroy minerals so how do minerals form well minerals form through a wide variety of processes and in general there are three processes that form minerals it is called precipitation crystallization and deposition now precipitation occurs when a solid forms then falls out of solution and some examples of these are evapori deposits such as salt and the crystals that we see inside geodes now crystallization is similar to water freezing except this is when minerals are formed from a melted magma lava solution so an example would be a magma formation and deposition can happen as a result of biological processes such as water drilling organisms can transform dissolved material into mineral matter one example of that is calcium carbonate forming coral reefs so the precipitation of mineral matter or ions occur most commonly when salt water body typically inland bodies of water like for example the great salt lake in utah can form evaporates and when this mineral rich water reaches saturation the ions within it begin to bond forming crystalline solids that we call salts that then settle out of solution some common evaporate deposits include halite remember halite sodium chloride our wonderful table salt this is how table salt is formed through precipitation silvite is another example of an evaporate deposit and it is potassium chloride similar to our halite sodium chloride and then we have gypsum now worldwide we can actually find many extensive evaporate deposits some exceeding hundreds of meters in thickness and these deposits provide evidence that there were ancient seas that have long since evaporated now one great example of that can be seen here in this image this is an image of white sands national park in new mexico and it is direct evidence that there used to be a shallow tropical sea in this region that has long since evaporated forming these beautiful white sands that we now see now minerals can also precipitate from slowly moving groundwater and groundwater can fill fractures or voids and rocks and sediments one great example of this is a geode geodes forming cavities in rocks such as limestone and volcanic rocks the slowly moving groundwater deposits dissolved mineral matter inside these voids and this produces some of the most beautiful forms of quartz that we see in geodes now the crystallization of minerals from molten rock is a process similar to water freezing although a little bit more complex the atoms inside the melted material are very mobile and hot but as it cools the atoms start to slow down and they begin chemically combining with one another this is the process that produces igneous rocks that consist of interground crystals which we will talk about in much greater detail in the igneous rocks module but this is the second way that minerals can form through crystallization and then finally minerals can form due to deposition in one way minerals can be deposited is as a result of a biological process now water dwelling organisms can transform substantial quantities of dissolved material into mineral matter for example corals can create large quantities of marine limestone which are rocks composed of the mineral calcite they absorb calcium ions from the seawater and then they use it to secrete external skeletons which are composed of that calcium carbonate or calcite over time these small organisms are capable of creating massive limestone structures known as coral reefs other marine invertebrates like clams and oysters can also secrete shells composed of this calcite and some of them use another mineral called aragonite when their remains are buried they become major components of the sedimentary rock limestone which again we will talk about later in the sedimentary rocks module now some microorganisms like tiny diatoms and radiolaryns can even produce glass-like skeletons and they produce it using the same process but forming silicon dioxide or quartz instead of that calcite and these are the main components of rocks such as chert or flint again these topics will come up again when we review sedimentary rocks now minerals can even form from deposition near volcanic vents or fumaroles where it sublimates from a stream of hot gases like sulfur that i have shown here now there are three general processes that can destroy minerals we can melt minerals dissolve minerals or there are various other chemical reactions that can actually destroy minerals there's a considerable range of melting temperatures for different compositions of minerals all the silicates are molten at about 1200 degrees celsius now different places on earth where we can facilitate the destruction of minerals by melting would be at plate boundaries such as divergent plate boundaries and convergent plate boundaries with subduction we will talk a lot more about the melting and cooling of minerals and rocks later on when we get to the igneous rocks module but melting minerals is one way we can destroy them a second way is by dissolving them water is a solvent that dissolves minerals from the rocks and when it comes into contact with it when water such as rain water mixes with carbon dioxide in the atmosphere or even air pockets within the soil a weak acid solution is created called carbonic acid over time this carbonic acid flows through the cracks of some rocks dissolving the minerals over time this process is called carbonation and it will come up again in the weathering module and we can also destroy minerals by various other chemical reactions chemical reactions or chemical weathering is the weakening and subsequent disintegration of a rock and its minerals by certain chemical reactions now these reactions include oxidation and hydrolysis these processes can destroy minerals and alter the nature of the rock's mineral composition oxidation is the reaction of a rock's minerals with oxygen iron barren minerals will rust hydrolysis is a chemical reaction caused by water water can change the chemical composition and the size of minerals in a rock making them less resistant to weathering we will talk more about these processes in the weathering module later on in the semester next we're going to go ahead and talk about the two different categories of minerals silicate minerals and non-silicate minerals

