howdy everyone we are now going to get into a little bit about mineral classification starting with silicate minerals all silicate minerals contain oxygen and silicon and most of them contain one or more of the other common elements the structure of every silicate mineral includes the silicon oxygen tetrahedron in this structure we have four oxygen ions that are covalently bonded to a silica ion which you can see is much smaller and together they form this tetrahedron which is this pyramid-shaped structure remember how i showed you the crystal form of quartz and how it had that pyramid-shaped appearance well this is exactly why quartz is just made of sio 4 this tetrahedron tetrahedron is quite complex ions and has a net charge of negative four this means to become electrically balanced they will usually bond with a positively charged metal ion one of the most simplest silicate structures consists of independent tetrahedra that have four oxygen ions bonded to positive ions such as the ions of magnesium iron and calcium with a plus two charge the mineral olivine is a great example of this these kind of silicates form hard dense equidimensional crystals that lack cleavage now sio4 tetrahedra can link to one another in a variety of configurations and we call this polymerization this accounts for the high variety of silicate minerals it is achieved by sharing one two three or all four oxygen atoms with an adjacent tetrahedra and tetrahedra can then form single chains double chains sheet structures or three-dimensional frame works let's take a look at what some of these structures look like as silica structures change from isolated silica tetrahedra like an a on the left two chains like in b and c to sheet structures like in d and then to frameworks like an e of silica tetrahedra the ratio of silica atoms to oxygen atoms increases as you move from a to e in the most common silicate structure all four oxygen ions are shared producing a complex three-dimensional framework examples of this include quartz and feldspars which are both commonly found in continental crust now except for quartz the basic structure of most silicate minerals have a net negative charge therefore metal ions are usually required to bring the overall charge into balance and they are used to hold these structures together the positively charged ions of iron magnesium potassium sodium aluminum and calcium are most often linked to these silicate structures as a general rule of thumb the covalent bonds between the silicon and the oxygen are stronger than the ionic bonds that hold one silicate structure to the next this creates properties that we talked about such as cleavage and to some extent this also dictates the hardness of the mineral now most silicates form from molten rock cooling and crystallizing the feldspars are the most common silicate group and make up more than 50 percent of earth's crust quartz is the second most abundant mineral in the continental crust and the only common mineral made completely of silicon and oxygen now silicates can be divided into two groups we call them light or non-ferromagnesian and dark ferromagnesium groups so here are just some of the most common silicate minerals we have olivine which is that green mineral see we have ogite which is a pyroxene we have hornblende which is an amphibole there's biotite and muscovite which are both micas we have our feldspar group like potassium feldspar and then we have our quartz now if you take the lab portion of this class you will probably get to work with all of these minerals in person and you will be asked to identify these using mineral properties now here's some of the most common silicate minerals in the crust again feldspars account for nearly 50 percent of the minerals found in in the crust and feldspars can be split up into plagioclase feldspars and potassium feldspars and the second most abundant is quartz at 12 percent and then we have pyroxenes which include agite we have micas amphiboles which include hornblende clay minerals and then other silicates so silicate minerals account essentially for 92 percent of the minerals found in the crust whereas the non-silicate minerals which we'll talk about in the next video only account for eight percent all right so now i mentioned that we can split silicates into two groups based on light and dark let's start with the light ones the light silicates which we can call them non-ferromagnesian that's a really long word what does that mean ferro means iron magnesium means magnesium and non means doesn't contain so light silicates do not contain iron or magnesium so light silicates tend to be lighter in color they also have a specific gravity of approximately 2.7 so they're not as dense they have a low density now these silicates can contain varying amounts of aluminum potassium calcium and sodium but the important part is that they lack iron and magnesium the feldspar group kind of falls in this category they're the most common mineral group they form under a wide range of temperatures and pressure they exhibit two directions of perfect cleavage at 90 degrees and the two most common members are orthoclase which is potassium feldspar and plagioclase which is sodium and calcium feldspar and if you take the lab portion of this class you'll see these both again light silicates are going to be light in color low in density with a lower melting point making them easier to melt and are commonly found in continental crust here's just some images of some of those common feldspar minerals these are considered our light silicates here on the top we have potassium feldspar and then on the bottom we have plagioclase feldspar quartz is another example of a light silicate it is the only common silicate composed entirely of oxygen and silicon however the impurities of other elements that are found is what causes the variety in color quartz is hard and very resistant to weathering they don't display cleavage but they do display concoil fracture due to the three-dimensional framework they often form hexagonal crystals and again their color is dictated by the impurities that are found within the crystalline structure muscovite is another common member of the light silicate minerals and is part of the mica family they have excellent cleavage in one direction muscovite can almost be peeled into sheets along this one plane of clothing muscovite occurs in thin sheets that are almost clear and they're used as glass during the middle ages muscovites produce the glimmering brilliance often seen in beach sand clay minerals are another example of light silicates and clay is a general term it's used to describe a variety of complex fine grained minerals that have sheet structures clays make up a large percentage of soil most originate as products of chemical weathering which we'll talk about in a later module kaolinite is a common clay mineral used to manufacture fine china and it's photographed here all right now on to the second group the dark silicates or ferromagnesian remember ferro meaning iron magnesium meaning magnesium so these silicates contain iron and or magnesium in their structure this makes them generally dark in color and has a specific gravity between 3.2 and 3.6 which makes them more dense olivine group minerals are included in the dark silicates and they have high temperature silicates so they have a higher melting point it's harder to melt this dark silicate group olivines are black to green in color they have a glassy luster and concoidal fracture they do not display cleavage they usually form small and rounded crystals and they're common in oceanic crust and constitute 50 of the earth's mantle now dark silicates the important part to remember these is they are dark in color because they contain iron and or magnesium this makes them more dense and requires a much higher temperature to melt and they are most commonly found in oceanic crust peroxide group is another group in the dark silicates and they are important components of dark colored igneous rocks angeli is the most common mineral in the pyroxene group it is black in color and has two distinct cleavages at nearly 90 degrees it is the dominant mineral and basalt amphibole group is very similar to the pyroxene group and they're hard to identify between the two one way to tell them apart is by their cleavage the amphibole group also has two perfect cleavages however they exhibit angles of about 120 degrees and 60 degrees warm blend is the most common mineral in this group it's usually black to dark green and again looks very similar in appearance to odd giant so you have to pay attention to those cleavages now if you take the lab portion of this class you'll probably explore that more in lab so here's just showing the differences between pyroxene and amphibole or agite and hornblende they're nearly identical but one way to tell them apart is the differing angles of their cleavage planes biotites and garnets are other common dark silicates biotites are iron-rich member of the mica family they're very similar to the muscovite that i showed earlier except for these contain magnesium and iron making them darker in color but they still have excellent cleavage in one direction and produce this sheet-like structure garnets are composed of individual tetrahedra linked by metallic ions very similar to olivine garnets have glassy luster they lack cleavage and have concoidal fracture also similar to olivine the colors vary but most often they're found to be brown red they have well developed crystals and have 12 diamond shaped faces here's a picture of a well-formed garnet crystal now that ends our lecture video on silicate minerals we are now going to move on to our next and final video of module 3 on non-silicate minerals

