howdy everyone and welcome to module 4 of this class in this module we're going to explore magma and igneous rocks but in this video i'm just going to barely scratch the surface just to kind of introduce the topic to you now magma is completely or partly molten rock and it's located beneath the earth's surface which when it's cold solidifies into igneous rocks igneous rocks are composed mainly of the silicate minerals we talked about last week magma is the parent material of igneous rocks and magma is formed by the partial melting in the earth's crust which we will talk about in much more greater detail later on in this module most magmas consist of three materials there's a liquid component or we call it a melt and this liquid melt is composed mainly of mobile ions of those eight most common elements in the earth's crust like remember silicon and oxygen but also aluminum potassium calcium sodium and iron and magnesium we can also have a solid component and this solid component consists of silicate mineral crystals remember minerals are solid and as the magma body begins to cool the size of the solid component will grow and we'll talk about this process again in much greater detail later and then we also have a gas component which we call volatiles volatiles are the materials that vaporize or form a gas at the surface and these are most commonly found as water vapor carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide now the volatiles can exist dissolved in the liquid melt or they can exist as gas bubbles within the melt now as magma begins to cool we start to form crystalline rock by a process we call crystallization which we briefly introduced last module crystallization is essentially the reverse event of melting so you can kind of think of it as freezing in a way as a magma crystallizes it results in those mobile ions that begin to slow as it cools and as these mobile ions slow they start to form a systematic arrangement in an orderly pattern and they begin forming mineral crystals now silicon and oxygen atoms usually link together first to start forming those lovely silicon oxygen tetrahedra that i'm sure all of you missed dearly from last week as it continues to cool and heat is lost those tetrahedras start forming and joining to each other and they even start joining to other ions in the mill to form crystal nuclei so the minerals that form the earliest end up having the most space to grow and have a better chance to develop those beautiful crystal faces than the minerals that start to form later on in the process igneous rocks are composed of interlocking crystals that were formed during the process of crystallization here is an example of an igneous rock that was formed from the crystallization of magma here you can see several minerals in its texture those gray and glassy grains are quartz most of the white crystals you see here are called plagioclase feldspar while the pink ones are potassium feldspar calcium is what actually gives it the pink color and then the black minerals you see here are mostly amphibole like the horn blend we saw in the last module and this rock pictured here is a common igneous rock called granite you've probably seen it before so as we will get into much more detail later on in the videos igneous rocks form in two basic settings they can form from the crystallization of magma at depth which means below the earth's surface and form what we call intrusive igneous rocks or sometimes we call them plutonic rocks these rocks can be found at the surface if over time the rock above is eroded away or something happens like a huge plate tectonic process of mounting building that uplifts these rocks to the surface but the rocks are formed below the earth's surface igneous rocks can also be formed by the solidification of lava or from volcanic debris after a volcanic eruption these rocks are called extrusive because they are found at or above the earth's surface we sometimes refer to these rocks as volcanics in the next two videos we will explore further how we actually classify igneous rocks

