can flow now why is that well heat can break bonds between atoms which makes them easier to flow past one another so the higher the temperature is the more atomic bonds will be broken and the easier it can flow and the lower the viscosity now you can also change the viscosity of a magma to lava by changing its silica content if you increase silica content you will also increase the viscosity remember an increase in silica content leads to an increase in viscosity this means the more silica you have in your melt the harder it's going to be to flow why is that well silica resists flow so if you increase the silica you will increase that resistance of flow and increase the viscosity so if we have a felsic magma and a mafic magma at the same temperature which one will have the higher viscosity the felsic magma would have the highest viscosity because it has the highest silica content these topics will come up again when we discuss volcanoes and volcanic eruptions so in summary we can tell a whole lot about igneous rocks just by looking at them and you can tell in igneous rock's composition by just simply looking at its color in general light colored igneous rocks contain a lot of light silicates and we consider them felsic because they're silica rich now dark colored igneous rocks contain a lot of dark silicates that we consider mafic which are rich in magnesium and iron and just by looking at a rock's color we can even tell a lot about the magma's behavior because we know what the composition probably was now with felsic rocks or light colored rocks that was probably formed by felsic or granitic magma and granitic magma has a lower temperature and a higher viscosity it's thicker now dark colored igneous rocks are probably mafic in composition which means the magma was probably mafic or basaltic in composition as well and basaltic magma has a higher temperature and a lower viscosity they flow much easier now these properties are really important when we study volcanic e