howdy everyone we are now going to move on to how we classify rocks based on their rock texture now remember when i showed this slide when we talked about the rock cycle and i mentioned that igneous rocks can be classified into two groups called intrusive and extrusive and these groups describe where they form now when they're formed by the cooling of magma and magma is the unerupted melted material beneath the earth's surface we call that intrusive now when igneous rocks are formed by the cooling of lava and lava is the erupted material above the earth's surface we call that extrusive so extrusive igneous rocks are formed after an eruption where intrusive igneous rocks are formed below the earth's surface when magma is allowed to cool slowly over time now we can tell a whole lot about a rock and where it's formed based on its texture and that's what this video is going to go over the texture of an igneous rock can tell us if it's extrusive or intrusive so i'll start with our intrusive igneous rocks remember sometimes we call them platonic now the easiest way to remember intrusive igneous rocks is that they form inside the earth and because they're forming inside the earth they have much more time to cool slowly because they're not in direct contact with the much cooler atmosphere above they're insulated deep under now underneath the ground so these rocks are able to cool much more slowly over time and because of that the minerals begin to crystallize in that magma and they have much more time to grow and much more space to grow and this creates a texture we call phaneritic and phaneritic is just a fancy word for coarse grained texture and here i have two photographs of intrusive igneous rocks i have a felsic version of one remember felsic light in color is our pink granite here on the left now when you look at granite you can see that it is full of many different minerals because the crystals are coarse grained and we can see them easily with the naked eye and that's because granite formed underneath the earth's surface and it cooled slowly over time it's an intrusive rock now over on the right is an intermediate version of an intrusive rock called diuret remember intermediate means that it's in between felsic and mafic and sometimes it can have this salt and pepper appearance like the diorite shown here now this diorite you can see has at least two different types of minerals because you can see two different types dark colored and light colored very easily with the naked eye they're very coarse grained crystals and the reason why they're coarse grained is because they were formed inside the earth and they cold much more slowly over time now the slower the cooling the bigger the crystals now extrusive igneous rocks the easiest way to remember extrusive is they form on the exterior of the earth because they are forming above the earth they cool much more quickly because they are in direct contact with the atmosphere which is much cooler so extrusive igneous rocks are cooling much more quickly so that means they don't have as much time for those minerals and crystals to really develop into a coarse grain texture our extrusive igneous rocks have a texture called a phonetic aphanitic is just a fancy word for fine grain it means the crystals are pretty small and hard to see we can also get a texture called vesicular vesicular is just a kind of spongy texture which i have shown here in the center and it's showing preserved gas bubbles now rocks that exhibit this vesicular texture code very fast so fast that the gas didn't even have time to fully escape the melt so the gas bubbles were preserved in the solid rock now another texture that we see in extrusive rocks is called glassy and it looks exactly like that it looks like glass or volcanic glass obsidian which is pictured here on the right is one example of that now glassy rocks are extrusive rocks that formed extremely fast so fast that sometimes when this material is erupted from a volcano that it almost cools in the atmosphere before it even hits the ground and because it cools extremely fast there's literally no time for any mineral crystals to develop within that melt so it preserves that glassy texture now what exactly do i mean by texture texture is used to describe the overall appearance of a rock based on the size shape and arrangement of the mineral grains and they can reveal a great deal about the environment which it formed texture or really the grain size is a direct reflection of the cooling rate the more time a magma or lava has to cool the larger the crystals will be the amounts of silica can also to a lesser extent influence texture because silica rich minerals tend to be the first to crystallize in a melt and the amount of dissolved gases within a magma and lava can also influence the texture now here's a great diagram showing all the different textures that we can see in igneous rocks now here on the diagram in a you see a glassy texture this is composed of unordered atoms and resembles a dark manufactured glass that's because it formed so quickly that it had no time for any minerals to crystallize out of that melt before it was solidified obsidian which is what's photographed there is a natural glass and it's usually formed when highly silica rich magmas solidify very rapidly obsidian is an extrusive igneous rock we know that because of its glassy texture now below that in b we have something called a porphyritic texture which i haven't talked about yet but i'll show it again later in this video but a porphyritic texture composes of two distinctly different crystal sizes so you can see in this rock in b there are some large crystals but these large crystals are in a very fine-grained matrix so we have fine-grained and coarse-grained minerals together in a rock and this kind of rock forms whenever at first the magma is allowed to cool slowly but then something happens that makes it cool much more quicker so that's how we get these two distinctly different crystal sizes and we call it porphyritic now below that in c we have phaneritic again phaneritic's just a fancy word for coarse grain texture and here the mineral grains are large enough to be identified without a microscope they're all coarse-grained and phaneritic rocks are considered intrusive igneous rocks because they're formed inside the earth now moving on to the right side of this diagram and d this is an example of a vesicular texture and it's a pumice vesicular texture is shown in extrusive rocks that form on the exterior of the earth's surface and this extrusive rock contains voids that's left by the gas bubbles that escape as the lava solidify so it forms very quickly that it doesn't even have time for that melt to settle when the gas is escaping so it preserves those gas bubbles in the solid rock and pumice is a frothy volcanic glass that displays a vesticular texture so it's just like our obsidian except for it's very frothy it's full of a lot of gas but it forms very quickly to the point where it doesn't have time for any minerals or crystals to really grow now below that an e we have an example of a pyroclastic or sometimes we call it fragmental texture now i haven't talked about this one either but i'll talk about it in later in the video the pyroclastic textures are produced by the consolidation of fragments that may include ash once molten blobs or large angular blocks that were ejected for an explosive volcanic eruption so these are extrusive rocks and they tell us a lot about how a volcano erupted when we see pyroclastic textured rocks we know there must have been a violent eruption now in our last example in f this is an a phonetic textured rock remember ethnic is just a fancy word for fine grained texture aphonetic textures are composed of crystals that are too small for the individual minerals to be identified without a microscope so there are indeed crystals interlocked within this texture we just need a tech we just need a microscope to observe them they're fine grain so a phonetic textured rocks are considered extrusive igneous rocks they form on the exterior of the earth's surface and they cool much more quickly than they would below the earth's surface so here's just some more detail on those textures that we can see now we have lots of different types of igneous textures that we just were introduced to in the last slide and the rate of choline tends to be the dominant factor now aphanitic or fine grain texture is when we have a rapid rate of cooling this produces microscopic crystals phaneritic texture or coarse grain texture is a result of slow cooling and this produces large visible crystals and porphyritic texture is when you have large crystals which we sometimes call phenocrysts that are embedded in a matrix of smaller crystals which we call a ground mass and rocks with this texture are called porphyry here's another example of a porphyritic texture you can see here the phenocrysts are the white crystals in this mass whereas the ground mass are much smaller dark colored crystals this is an example of a porphyritic texture and this can happen when a melt is allowed to cool slowly at first but then the colon speeds up now the other types of igneous textures are vesicular texture and this occurs when rocks contain voids left by gas bubbles in the lava and it's a common feature of extrusive igneous rocks glassy textures are the result of very rapid cooling and this is happens when the ions are frozen in place before they can unite in an orderly crystalline structure it has no time for it to really develop into any mineral grains pyroclastic or fragmental texture forms when the consolidation of individual rock fragments are rejected during explosive eruptions so these kind of rocks can tell us a lot about how a volcano erupted texture is usually the result of a very violent eruption and then we have another texture we haven't talked about yet called pegmatitic an