<details><summary>Show Transcript</summary>

howdy everyone and welcome to the video in module 4 where we will be discussing making magma in order to understand the origin of magma we must first introduce the geothermal gradient the geothermal gradient is the increase in temperature with depth and on average every kilometer deep we go into the earth we see about an increase of 25 degrees celsius as you will soon see this means that the rocks in the lower crust and upper mantle are near their melting points they are unable to melt on their own and require some kind of tectonic process to actually trigger the melting by either reducing their melting point and there are three ways we can facilitate melting and they are by decreasing the pressure adding water or increasing the temperature of the crustal rocks so here is a wonderful diagram showing us that geothermal gradient the x-axis is showing us temperature which is increasing from left to right the y-axis is showing us depth which increases from top to bottom so as we go deeper into the earth we reach deeper and deeper depths of below of this chart now the solid red curved line that's the geothermal gradient and you can see that the temperature is rising with an increase in depth the area that's shaded in green represents where we would find solid rock the orange area is where we can expect to find partial melting to begin and the yellow area is where we would expect complete melting as you can see here at the depth of the upper asthenosphere the red curve which again is our geothermal gradient is close to that orange zone but everything in here is still solid remember only the outer core is liquid the rest of the interior of the earth is solid so how in the world is magma produced then well since in the upper asthenosphere we are so close to the boundary of partial melting we only require a slight change in conditions to cause mantle rock to partially melt this again is caused by decreasing the pressure which we call decompression melting adding water to lower the melting point or by increasing the temperature decompression melting occurs when we reduce the confining pressures enough to lower the melting temperature what does this mean well as you can imagine the deeper we go into the earth the more pressure we can experience and this pressure can make it harder to melt things because as you increase the pressure you typically increase the melting point as well now if we were to take very hot rocks that were very deep inside the earth and suddenly brought them to a shallower depth their melting point would be lower enough to allow them to begin to melt this is a process that's commonly found at divergent plate boundaries and hot spots here's a nice diagram that shows that decompression melting so here on the x-axis we have increasing temperature as you move left to right on the y-axis we have increasing pressure from top to bottom the green area is where we would expect to find solid material and the yellow area is where we can expect to find liquid the red line is called the melting curve you can see here that the melting temperature increases with depth but if we were to take hot solid rock from deeper below and just move it upwards we could rise it enough to a depth that had a lower melting temperature and the substance would then be able to melt again this is exactly what is happening at mid-ocean ridges as the hot materials rising upwards from the mantle facilitating melting and then forming that new oceanic crust the same thing is happening at hot spots where we have mantle plumes bringing hot mantle material upwards to lower pressures which then facilitate its melting and forms volcanoes in both of these cases we have mantle material being melted which makes the magma and the lava basaltic in composition now here's another diagram showing that decompression melting and this is being shown at a mid-ocean ridge remember at mid-ocean ridges we have hot mantle material that's rising upwards so as that material is rising upwards it's very hot but we're bringing it to less pressure which means it can melt at a lower temperature so because this material is super hot it begins to melt because we've lowered the pressure this is called decompression melting and we're forming basaltic magma and that basaltic magma is buoyant it's less dense than the surrounding rock so it's going to continue to rise and eventually reach the surface of the earth and form that new oceanic crust another factor that influences the melting is the water content water and other volatiles act on a rock the same way that salt acts on ice water causes the rock to melt at lower temperatures just like the throat the salt that we throw outside on an icy day enhances melting on the icy sidewalk this probably isn't the best analogy to use here at texas a m because we don't really see very much snow or ice here this introduction of water to generate magma mainly occurs at convergent plate boundaries with subduction zones where we have those cold slabs of oceanic lithosphere that is subducting into the mantle not only is the oceanic crust over lane with water but as the new hot crust that is being formed near the ridge cools it interacts with all this water as the sea water circulates through the new hot crust the water becomes hot enough to react with the layers of basalt and then it forms hydrated minerals that contain water in their chemical makeup so when a slab of this hydrated mineral rich oceanic crust reaches a subduction zone it will begin to descend into the hot mantle below and as this plate sinks it starts to warm up and it causes all these hydrated minerals to release their water in a metamorphic process we call dehydration because water is buoyant and less dense than its surrounding it will begin to migrate upwards into a wedge of hot mantle that lies directly above the subducting plate this addition of the water will lower the melting temperature enough to facilitate melting and generate basaltic magma the addition of the water and the other volatiles like carbon dioxide make this basaltic magma a little bit more explosive than the magmas generated by decompression melting now here's a diagram that shows that melting by adding water you can see here the oceanic place plate being subducted underneath the continental plate and as that oceanic plate is subducted and reaches temperatures that are high enough for the water to be released from the hydrated minerals and that water migrates upwards into the mantle lowering the melting point and facilitating that melting and that's how we have basaltic magma forming and then that basaltic magma is buoyant it's less dense than its surrounding so it's going to begin to rise this is how we facilitate melting by just the addition of water now basaltic magmas usually erupt on the ocean floor to produce sea mounds or eventually form volcanic islands like hawaii however in continental settings this magma often ponds beneath the very thick and low density crustal rocks these heat from the magma cannot be hot enough to facilitate the melting of the continental crust material and form felsic magma if these felsic magmas reach the surface they can be some of the most explosive volcanic eruptions in earth's history felsic magma and continental rift zones are one example of heat transfer melting so are the super volcanoes found at continental hot spots things can get a little more complicated geologists have observed that over time a single volcano can extrude different types of lava to understand why this can happen we need to take a look at bowen's reaction series bowen's reaction series describes the order in which minerals will begin to crystallize in a melt the first to crystallize is olivine as the melt begins to cool further calcium-rich plagioclase will begin to crystallize as well like pyroxene and then amphibole and so on during this complex crystallization process the composition of the remaining liquid portion is constantly changing for example once a third of the melt has been crystallized the remaining melt will have very little iron magnesium and calcium left here's a figure that shows bones reaction series very nicely here at the top you can see the excess access is representing temperature with our hottest temperatures on the left and it's cooling as we move to the right so as you can see here in bones reaction series olivine is the first mineral to begin to crystallize it begins to crystallize at right around 1200 degrees or a little bit less the next mineral to crystallize is pyroxene and as you can see olivine and pyrroxine these are the minerals that first begin to cool and crystallize and these are ultramafic and mafic minerals that means the remaining melts after our olivine and pyroxene have crystallized will be more felsic in nature after olivine and pyroxene we then have amphibole biotite mica and the rest of our plagioclase feldspar once we start to get even colder that's when we'll start to have more felsic minerals forming like potassium feldspar muscovite mica quartz and so forth so bowen demonstrated that minerals crystallized from magma in a systematic fashion as a function of temperature but how does bowen's findings explain the great diversity we see in igneous rocks at one or more stages during the crystallization of magma a separation of various components can occur one mechanism that can cause this to happen is caused crystal settling this process occurs when the earlier form minerals like olivine and pyroxenes are dense and heavier than the liquid portion and begin to sink towards the bottom of the magma chamber when the remaining melt solidifies either in place or at another location it will form a rock with a different mineral composition that is different than the parent magma the formation of a magma body having a chemical composition that is different from that of the parent magma is called magmatic differentiation here's a figure that shows the process of crystal settling in figure a we have a magma that has a mafic composition that erupts and leaves a layer of basaltic rock at the surface then at b the cooling of the magma causes crystals of the earliest minerals to form and settle out then in c we could have another eruption but the remaining melt would be enriched with silica since the magnesium iron and calcium already started to crystallize and settle out this leads to a much more explosive eruption and leaves a layer of silica rich rock at the surface recent work actually indicates that magmatic differentiation cannot account for the entire compositional spectrum of igneous rocks once a magma body forms the incorporation of foreign material can also change its composition this is called assimilation in assimilation we have magma pushing upwards that cracks the crust around it causing fractures the magma can then be injected into these fractures and begin to dislodge rock this displaced rock is then melted and incorporated into the melt changing the overall chemical composition of the magma another means by which the composition of magma can be altered is called magma mixing magma mixing can occur during the ascent of two chemically distinct magma bodies as the more buoyant mass overtakes the more slowly rising body once they are joined convective flow stirs the tube magmas generating a single mass that has an intermediate composition incomplete melting of rocks is known as partial melting this process produces most of the magmas during partial melting the melt is enriched with ions from minerals with the lowest melting temperature partial melting of ultramafic rocks yields mafic magmas partial melting of mafic rocks makes intermediate magmas and partial melting of intermediate rocks makes felsic magmas and again this partial melting process produces most of our magmas here's a figure that's just showing that partial melting you have a source wrong and it's not all being melted at the same time with partial melting you could have magma being generated from the source rock that is felsic in composition but the mafic minerals remain a solid most magmas that are erupt are basaltic or magma mafic magma most originate from partial melting or mantle rocks at oceanic ridges these melts are called primary or primitive magmas because they have not yet evolved now and acidic magma can form in two ways it can form by magmatic differentiation of mantle derived basaltic magma or can be formed by basaltic magmas assimilating crustal rock granitic magmas most often form when basaltic magma ponds beneath the continental crust heating and melting the much lower melting temperature felsic minerals it can also be formed from magmatic differentiation of antacidic magma here's a nice diagram showing the formation of felsic magma at the bottom of this figure at 1 we're seeing partial melting of peridotite that's generating basaltic magma due to decompression melting we have hot mantle material rising up here from the asthenosphere below which is at bringing it to a lower pressure facilitating that melting but what we're actually partially melting is the mantle itself which it consists of peridotite which is basaltic in composition and then that basaltic magma is less dense than its surrounding it's more buoyant so it's going to begin to rise upwards like we see here in two the basaltic magma rises through the lithospheric mantle and it continues to rise until we reach number three where we have the basaltic magma ponding underneath the less dense crustal rock and then at number four we get partial melting of that continental crust that the basaltic magma is ponding underneath this generates magma with a more felsic composition and this is how we can form felsic magma now in the next and final video of this module we will discuss more about magma movement and emplacement

