howdy everyone and welcome to the last video of module 4. in this video we're going to be exploring how magma moves and some of the structures that are created from this magma movement and placement even though volcanic eruptions can be amazing events most magma actually crystallizes that depth without ever being erupted when magma rises through the earth's crust it forces the pre-existing rock or sometimes we refer to this pre-existing rock as the host rock or country rock to become displaced and the structures that result from this emplacement of magma into the host rock are called intrusions or plutons since these features form deep within the earth we are only able to study them after an uplifting or erosion event that brings them to the surface which often times happens millions of years after their formation now these intrusions or plutons can occur in a variety of sizes and shapes we will begin exploring some of these throughout this entire video there are two different classifications of plutons based on their shape and their orientation relative to the host rock we have tabular plutons which are table like and these can cut across existing structures or be parallel to the features we can also have massive plutons which essentially are just a blob shape here's a figure that shows some of these plutons very nicely in a we can see how volcanism is responsible for these intrusive bodies these blobs are the magma chambers that once cold will form plutons you can also see where magma is forced upwards in long linear pipes that cut through the existing layers of rock these are called dikes sometimes magma will travel horizontally along these layers these are called sills then we also have lacoliths which is shown right here and lacklus we will talk about later on in this video in this figure you can also see other terms like cinder cones composite cones and fissure eruptions which we will get into in the next module this figure is also a good one to study and can 