ind of look like large three-dimensional mud cracks in igneous rocks all right so now we're going to get into the pluton blobs batholiths are the largest intrusive structure they can occur as linear structures that are several hundred kilometers long the sierra nevada batholis for example is a continuous granitic structure that forms most of the backbone of the sierra nevada mountains in california an even bigger example can be found along the coast mountains of western canada and even into southern alaska that extends over 1100 miles even though some of these bath lifts are just downright massive the majority of them are actually 10 kilometers thick or less we also tend to find them composed of mainly felsic rock like granite to intermediate types and very rarely find mafic batholis we in general call these bodies of batholis when they are exposed at the surface for over a hundred square kilometers and we then call them stocks when they are smaller than that here is a map showing these bath lists made of granite along the western margin of north america with the sierra nevadas shown here as well as the coastal range up north now lachlans can form when magma is forcibly injected between sedimentary layers of host rock and start to actually deform the rock above it as it expands you can think of these as over-inflated sills here you can see mount ellen in utah which is found in the henry mountains mount ellen is just one of five peaks that make up this smaller range mount ellen is composed of crystalline rock that was once formed deep underground this intrusive body is called a stock and if you look at the illustrated version below you can see other structures such as dikes and cells in front of mount ellen and to the left in this image we can see another uplifted feature this is an example of a lachlan and it was formed when a cell became over inflated and literally started pushing the rock above it upwards and folded the layers around it now what happens to all this rock that is being displaced when magma forces its way through while depending on the tectonic environment geologists have proposed several mechanisms to solve this problem very deep in the earth rocks tend to be more ductile in nature and are able to make room for this magma by being pushed aside and bending we call this shouldering as magma nears the surface though it starts to encounter rock that is much cooler and more brittle this rock is not easily pushed aside instead the rock will sometimes break and become dislodged and sink through the magma in a process called stoping we find evidence of this process in xenoliths which are suspended blocks of country rock found within plutons here is a photo showing an example of a xenolith you can see here that the xenolith is made of very different material than the surrounding material this xenolith is actually made of dark mafic rock that was incorporated into a felsic magma remember magma can also melt and assimilate some of this hose dark as well but in this case the magma likely wasn't hot enough to completely melt the surrounding mafic material now this concludes the videos for module 4. you should now have all the information you need to complete this module's participation activity before taking the quiz i highly recommend you read chapter 4 in your textbook especially sections 4.4 4.5 and 4.7 before your quiz as always please reach out to me with any questions this module really set the stage nice for our next module on volcanoes and volcanic hazards igneous rocks are important to study because the composition of these rocks can tell us a lot about the composition of the magmas or lavas that formed them and thus igneous rocks give us clues on how a volcano will erupt in the future that create the many hazards we will talk about that impact life on earth good luck on module 4's quiz and i will see you again in module 5.

