e not expected to erupt in the future and they're not even capable of producing an eruption anymore now i like to show this and talk about the anatomy of a volcano because there are different terms that we use like in the last module we talked about magma a lot remember magma is the molten rock that usually contains some crystals and dissolved gases under the earth's surface but in this module we're going to focus a lot more on lava and lava quite simply is magma that has been erupted onto the earth's surface now remember we had different compositions of magma and the same is true for lava as well now we can lump the compositions of lava into three different types basaltic which remembers mafic and acidic which is an intermediate composition and rhyolitic which is felsic now basaltic lava usually the source is from the upper mantle which is what makes it mafic these lavas tend to have a low viscosity but the highest temperature because it requires a higher temperature to melt these types of minerals now basaltic lavas tend to have one to two percent gas content so it's the lowest gas content of the three main types of lava and they're mafic so they only have about 50 percent of silica minerals now for this module the important part to remember is that basaltic lava flows are the least explosive types now antacidic lavas are intermediate in composition so they have about 60 silica now and acidic lavas the source tends to be ocean crust and sediments and it's the ocean crust that is mafic in composition and the sediments that are felsic which means this results in an intermediate composition now and acidic lavas tend to have a medium viscosity and they have about three to four percent gas content which makes them medium explosive so not as explosive as rhyolitic which we'll talk about in a moment but a little more explosive than our basaltic lava now rhyolitic lava is felsic in composition so they have about 70 silica and that's because the source is continental crust remember our continental crust is felsic in composition so rhyolytic lavas have a high viscosity and the lowest temperature of the three main types rhyolitic lavas have four to six percent gas content so they have the most gas content out of the three main types this along with other properties is what makes it the most explosive lava type now remember that these compositional differences in magmas and lavas also affect several other properties like viscosity i showed this slide in the last module but it's really important to review it again remember viscosity is the internal resistance to flow of a liquid and a magma or lava viscosity depends on the temperature and the composition now when we have an increase in temperature we tend to have a decrease in viscosity and when we have an increasing silica content we have an increase in viscosity now mafic magmas have the lowest silica remember mafic magmas have the lowest silica they also have the lowest gas content and erupt at the highest temperatures this makes mafic magmas have the lowest viscosity remember mafic magmas have a low viscosity now felsic magmas have the highest silica and they erupt at relatively lower temperatures they also have the highest gas content so this makes felsic magmas or lavas have the highest viscosity remember felsic lava has a high viscosity now different volcanoes can erupt in different styles and we have two main eruption styles and we're going to talk about each of these in more detail the two eruption types we have are explosive which is pretty self-explanatory and effusive ephesus just a fancy word for a gentler eruption or like a pouring out of lava so what determines the explosiveness of a volcano what's determining if we're going to get an explosive eruption versus an effusive eruption well there are two main factors that determine the explosiveness of a volcano there's magma type or lava type remember felsic intermediate and mafic and this describes really the amount of silica that is contained in a melt and the second property that determines the explosiveness of a volcano is that viscosity and viscosity kind of describes how easily gas can escape from the magmar or the lava so together the magma type and the viscosity are the controlling factors that determine how a volcano will erupt now effusive eruptions are those with low viscosities remember effusive eruptions have low viscosity so these effusive eruptions are those with low viscosity lavas and they are likely mafic in composition so see how it all kind of goes together now these eruptions are caused by the dissolved gases in the melt being released which then results in the magma starting to expand and eventually allowing it to escape and forming an eruption lava fountains are very common and these eruptions can last weeks months or even years kilauea in hawaii is a perfect example of that now these types of eruptions in general will form two main land forms and we call them shield volcanoes and flood basalts shield volcanoes have a low profile resembling a warrior shield laying on the ground it is formed by the eruption of highly fluid lava which has low viscosity hence the effusive eruption this type of lava can travel farther and forms thinner flows than the more viscous lava eruptions from other types of eruptive style ant forms now flood basalts are the result of a giant volcanic eruption or really a series of eruptions that cover very large stretches of land and we'll talk about both of these in more detail so shield volcanoes are the largest volcanoes in size now even though they are the largest the slope of the volcano is very gentle so they have a low profile again similar to a warrior shield being laid down flat on the ground now shield volcanoes are characterized by quiet non-explosive eruptions that we call effusive and they contain basaltic magma or basaltic lava remember basaltic lava is low in silica and low in viscosity allowing it to flow much farther distances now the eruptions consist mainly of lava flows but we also get some tephra and that's a term we're going to be talking about in another video later on in this module so here's a photo of a very famous shield volcano you may have seen it before again shield volcanoes it doesn't really stick out of the landscape as much as a more steeper volcano would because these slopes are very gentle but these volcanoes cover a huge vast of land this is monologue in hawaii mauna loa in hawaii is a shield volcano and it is the largest volcano that we have on earth here's a little more helpful of a figure that kind of shows the size of mona loa versus mount rainier now you may have seen photos of mount rainier mount rainier looks massive and the slopes are steep but in this figure we're showing the size of mount rainier which is in the middle of this figure at a height of a little over 14 000 feet next to mauna loa and mount rainier can fit inside monoloa now you might notice that mauna loa's height is 13 677 feet which is less than mount rainier and that's because when we talk about height we're talking about in reference to sea level now if you notice monoloa starts on the oceanic floor which is 19 000 feet deep here so add that to the height of mauna loa above the sea level and it makes it one massive monster now a flood basalt is the result of a gigantic volcanic eruption or a series of eruption that covers large stretches of land or the ocean floor with basaltic lava many flood basalts have been attributed to the onset of a hot spot reaching the surface of the earth via a mantle plume here's a map that shows some of the world's flood basalts we will explore these flood basalts in a little more detail later on in this module especially the columbia river flood basalts which you can see in north america but we also have many massive flood basalts like the siberian traps and asia and the deacon traps in india so these flood basalts actually form a significant portion of the earth's surface so we will explore this later on in a different video now explosive eruptions are associated with highly viscous lavas the dissolved gases are also released here but they tend to get trapped within the magma this causes a chain reaction that generates more gas bubbles and leads to a huge explosion i think a pop can that has been shaken up is finally being opened now these types of eruptions can expel particles of fragmented lava and gases at supersonic speeds that often evolves into an eruption column which you can see here in this photograph now explosive eruptions form their own type of landforms and in general we see three main types composite volcanoes cinder cones and calderas composite volcanoes which are sometimes referred to as stratovolcanoes are conical volcanoes they're shaped like a cone and that's because they're built up by many layers of hardened lava and tephra or ash that kind of gives it that steep profile now cinder cones are also conical shaped but they're made up of loose pyre classic fragments like ash or cinder that has been built up around a volcanic vent and calderas are large depressions formed when a volcano erupts and collapses think like you have a full balloon underneath the sandbox volcano and the balloon pops creating a depression in the volcano where the balloon once was the same thing happens with volcanoes except the magma chamber is your balloon and the pop is an eruption so here's a figure showing a composite volcano again these are also called stratovolcanoes and they are conical and shaped so they're shaped like a cone and you can see here the composite volcano is built up of many layers of hardened lava and tephra or ash here's an example of a strata volcano or composite volcano mount rainier mount rainier is a volcano in washington and in this image you can even see mount st helens in the background however this photo was taken before the 1980 eruption so mount st helens looks very different today but here both of th