 within it and forms that called caldera over time sometimes we can have a new volcano form in the middle of these calderas which we call volcanic cones or soma volcanoes but the important part to remember is that caldera formations are the result from a collapse of a composite volcano with an explosive eruption here's a great example of a caldera result of this type of caldera formation is crater lake crater lake national park is found in oregon it formed from a violent eruption and explosion of mount mazama over 7 000 years ago here's another image showing of crater lake and you could see in the middle of crater lake a new volcano started to form yellowstone is another great example of a caldera and the yellowstone national park almost sits in the middle of a giant caldera from the last explosive eruption of the yellowstone super volcano about 600 000 years ago now here's a figure i like to show at the end that shows the composite versus shield volcano versus cinder cones by size remember i said shield volcanoes are the largest volcano and it is shown at the top of this figure with our largest volcano on earth monoloa now even the smallest shield volcano that we have like mount kilimanjaro is still much larger than the largest stratovolcano or composite volcano like mount shasta mount fuji is considered a medium composite volcano but it looks like a baby in comparison to mauna loa in mount vesuvius which you may have heard about is very destructive but it is so tiny in scale next to the large shield volcanoes and then remember our cinder cones how i said they are much smaller our larger cinder cone sunset crater is shown there right underneath vesuvius and that's our largest cinder cone most cinder cones are much smaller than that now that we understand a little bit about the nature of volcanic eruptions we are going to take a look at the volcanic materials such as lava pyroclastics and volcanic gases

