howdy everyone and thank you for continuing on module 5. this is the second video in module 5 on volcanoes and volcanic hazards lots of material are rejected during a volcanic eruption such as lava pyroclastics and gases but in this video we are just going to focus on the lava flows remember there are three main types of lava mafic or basaltic intermediate or and acidic and felsic or rhiolytic most of the lava found on earth which is about 90 of it actually is basaltic and it is found erupting at oceanic ridges less than 10 percent is and acidic and found at volcanic chains and volcanic island arcs along plate convergent margins with subduction only about one percent is rhyolytic and found mostly in continental settings associated with hot gases and ash let's start with basaltic lava flow since they make up 90 of the earth's lavas and they make up almost 70 percent of the earth's surface there are three main forms of basaltic lava flows we call them pillow pahoe hoy and ah pillow lavas are the result of an outpouring of lava on the ocean floor the flow's outer skin quickly solidifies almost like freezing to form volcanic glass because of the drastic temperature changes between the hot magma below the earth's surface and the cool waters that are now above however the interior of the lava is able to still move forward and break through this hardened surface and begin the process over and over again this results in a lava flow composed of many tube-like structures called pillow lavas that are stacked on top of each other pillow lavas are extremely useful when studying earth's history because their presence indicates the lava flow formed below the surface of water ahoy hoy lava forms on land unlike the pillow lavas that form on the ocean floor ahoy hoy have smooth surfaces that sometimes resemble twisted braids of rope this is because pahoy hoy lavas are very hot and very fluid making them have a lower viscosity this allows them to flow over greater distances sometimes ahoy hoy lavas are also really nice to help us study past volcanic eruptions because when we find them we can infer which direction the lava was flowing at the time it formed for example here on this image we can see that the lava was flowing from the left to the right now the other lava flow that can occur on land is ah ah offloads have surfaces of rough jagged blocks with dangerously sharp edges that's because these lavas are very viscous this is because they occur at much colder temperatures than pahoehoe the hoihoe lavas can also transition into a lavas as it cools although the reverse isn't ever likely to happen remember viscosity increases as temperature decreases this increase in viscosity promotes bubble formation and the escaping gas bubbles can produce voids which we call vesicles and the surface now my earth science teacher in high school had a funny way of helping me remember the difference between pahoehoe and ah imagine you're walking over these lava flows and the sound you make if you were to walk across the jagged sharp flows of atta we would probably go ah the whole way across now if we walked across a smooth pahoehoe flow we would be much more relaxed like the word maybe this will help you remember too now the important thing to remember about pahoehoe and ah is that they are made out of the same composition the only difference between the two is their temperature which impacts their viscosity lavas of and acidic or intermediate composition form somewhat of a different lava flow known as block lava block lavas resemble a lava because they have a high viscosity block lavas tend to generate short but prominent flows their upper surface consists of largely massive detached blocks these blocks tend to be slightly curved with smooth surfaces instead of sharp and jagged like now remember the character of lava flows depends on viscosity basaltic lava is less viscous than antacidic and rhyolytic llama the more viscous alaba is the greater its resistance to flow for example honey is more viscous than water and acidic and rhyolitic lava are more viscous than basaltic lava now lava isn't the only thing that is released during an eruption in the next video we will talk about the other two components of interruption pyroclastics and volcanic gases

