howdy everyone in this video we're going to be exploring the additional material that is ejected from a volcanic eruption other than lava such as pyroclastic materials and volcanic gases the dissolved gases in magma are referred to as volatiles and make up about one to eight percent of the total weight of magma as the magma reaches the surface the pressure is reduced this allows the gases to start expanding and trying to escape most of these gases come in the form of water vapor followed by carbon dioxide or co2 and sulfur dioxide or so2 along with lesser amounts of hydrogen sulfide or h2s carbon monoxide co and nitrogen n2 although the percentage may be small the actual quantity of emitted gases contributes significantly to our planet's atmosphere and global warming the actual quantity of emitted gases can exceed thousands of tons per day volcanoes are also natural sources of air pollution now pyroclastic material or sometimes we just call them tephra are the pulverized rock and lava fragments that are ejected during an eruption these particles can range in size from fine dust to rocks the size of minivans the smallest form of pyroclastics or tephra is volcanic ash this is the result of when a gas-rich viscous magma erupts explosively as magma moves up in the vent gases rapidly expand generating a melt that resembles froth that flows from a bottle of champagne as the heated gases expand violently the froth is blown into fine glassy fragments we know as ash when the hot ash falls and fuses together it often creates a rock we called welded tough lapilli means little stones and is a fancy word for those cinders that make up the cinder cone lapilli can range in size from small beads to the size of walnuts now blocks are much much larger than lapille blocks are made of hardened lava that are greater than two and a half inches in diameter sometimes these hardened lava fragments can reach insane sizes bombs are the material that are also greater than two and a half inches in diameter but they are ejected as hot lava because they are not completely cold and are still in a semi-molten state when ejected they take on a streamlined shape as they are hurtled through the air almost like a football now ash can travel great distances very far away from the volcano thanks to their small size and light weight making it easier to be carried up into the atmosphere however blocks and bombs usually fall near the vent due to their size and weight but occasionally they have been found to be thrown great distances for example a bomb that was 20 feet long and weighed over 200 tons was blown over 2 000 feet from a vent during an eruption in japan of mount osama here is a nice figure showing the different types of volcanic material based on size again volcanic ash is the smallest with the diameter less than two millimeters lapilli are cinders between two millimeters and 64 millimeters in diameter or point eight two and a half inches which is probably easier for most of you to envision while volcanic blocks and bombs are more than two and a half inches our classic materials can be classified by texture and composition as well as by size for instance scoria is the term for vesicular ejecta produced most often during the eruption of basaltic magmas scoria are generally found in the sizes of lapilli and form our wonderful cinder cone volcanoes scoria are black to reddish brown fragments and get this color from the magnesium and iron rich magma during a basaltic eruption hummus on the other hand is produced when magmas with antacidic or rhyolytic composition erupt explosively pumice is usually lighter in color and less dense than scoria because they are made from more felsic material and have so many vesicles allowing it to float alright so here is a very nice summary that links magma composition with all the properties we have talked about so far such as silica content gas content eruptive temperature viscosity pyroclastics and landforms this graphic will 