ngton montana oregon idaho and even a little bit of nevada originated from one of the most highly effusive eruptions in the world the relatively flat features of solidified flood basalts which you can see here in the image on the right on the banks of the river are indicative of extremely low viscosity the many layers indicate many repeated eruptions this sequence is a classic example of a flood basalt activity that erupted more than 350 lava flows from the oldest one at the bottom 16.7 million years ago to the youngest flow on top 5.5 million years ago the eruptions originated from a series of linear fissures ranging from tens to hundreds of kilometers in length the magma that fed these massive eruptions may have come from a plume-like swelling from the mantle called a hot spot since the time of eruptions the north american plate has moved and the hot spot is now believed to reside beneath the yellowstone volcano lava domes are other volcanic landforms we see on earth lava domes are small dome-shaped masses composed of rhyolitic lava rhyolite eruptions are usually explosive but not always sometimes they produce these lava domes that erupt slowly over time as the thick rhyolitic viscous lava is squeezed from a bend it produces a dome-shaped mass collapses of these lava domes often produce powerful pyroclastic flows that we will get into later on in this module volcanic necks and pipes are other features that we see that stick out of the landscape associated with volcanoes a volcanic neck is the remains of a magma that's solidified inside a conduit a great example of that is shiprock in new mexico which is photographed here the reason that these features are exposed at the surface as hills ridges and mountains is because volcanic rocks are much more resistant to weathering and the surrounding rock over time was weathered away pipes are also a volcanic landform we see although they are rare they are conduits that originated in the mantle at depths exceeding 150 kilometers kimberlite pipes is where we can find diamonds and they are examples of these rare features in the next video we will explore in a little more detail the tectonic setting of volcanoes or where on earth we expect to find these destructive processes

