howdy everyone in this video we're going to be talking about the tectonic setting of volcanoes or where on earth we can find these things happening here's a nice figure showing the plate tectonic setting of volcanoes most of the earth's volcanic activity occurs at mid-ocean ridges which are found at divergent plate boundaries remember divergent plate boundaries from our plate tectonic module well all the information you learned in that module is going to be useful in this video the remainder occurs at convergent plate boundaries where we see most of our volcanoes and those are only at convergent plate boundaries above subduction zones and then we have a smaller amount that occur at hot spots which we've also talked about now i really like this slide because it very nicely summarizes all the plate tectonic settings of volcanoes but i'm going to get into more detail on each of these settings here in a moment but convergent margins have volcanoes only where we have subduction zones and these volcanoes produce and acidic magma which produce explosive eruptions and tend to lead to the formation of composite volcanoes some examples of that are mount saint helens mount vesuvius and mount fuji now divergent margins we mainly see volcanoes associated with mid-ocean ridges however we do have some on land and rift zones most of the volcanoes on divergent margins produce basaltic magma which often lead to quiet non-explosive eruptions that we call effusive and these types of eruptions more commonly produced shield volcanoes some examples of that are the volcanoes in iceland and the volcanic activity seen all along the mid-ocean ridge now another plate tectonic setting that we can see volcanoes are at hot spots but i separate these into two different kinds hot spots over oceanic crust in hot spots over continental crust hot spots over oceanic crust form due to a relatively stationary mantle plume and these result in basaltic magma and form shield volcanoes now these volcanoes are characterized by usually quiet non-explosive eruptions or those effusive eruptions great example of that is the hawaiian islands now hot spots underneath continental crust behave very differently they also form due to a relatively stationary mantle plume but instead of basaltic magma we have rhyolytic magma and these can result in caldera eruptions which produce some of the most explosive volcanoes on earth an example of that is yellowstone volcanoes at convergent margins only occur where we have subduction zones they are formed because of the volatile rich magmas that are generated by the melting due to the addition of volatiles these margins produce most of the volcanoes that we see on the earth's surface the magma produced here is mostly and acidic in composition or intermediate which can lead to explosive eruptions and composite volcanoes examples again include mount saint helens mount vesuvius and mount fuji now volcanoes at divergent plate boundaries are mostly found along mid-ocean ridges lavas erupted at mid-ocean ridges produces 70 of the earth's surface this is where that hot mantle material rises and leads to decompression melting which generates basaltic magma and eventually forms new ocean floor they produce mostly quiet non-explosive eruptions or effusive eruptions and form shield volcanoes not all diverging volcanoes are over oceanic crust though some are formed over continental crust like mount kilimanjaro and the continental rift zone of east africa continental rifts produce magma from decompression melting in the mantle but then felsic magma is produced by the melting of continental crusts which we sometimes call heat transfer melting oceanic hot spots are the result of a stationary mantle plume that produces basaltic magma by decompression melting and they form seamounts and shield volcanoes they are characterized by quiet non-explosive eruptions like the example of the hawaiian islands remember these hot spots can be stationary for very long periods of time like shown here under the pacific plate for over 80 million years right off the coast of the big island of hawaii is where we have the current hotspot sitting today but as the pacific ocean pacific plate has moved over top of this it has produced the entire chain of the hawaiian islands the hawaiian ridge shown on the sea floor and even the emperor sea mounts when we see sea mounts or remnants of shield volcanoes preserved on the earth's surface like in the hawaiian islands we can actually infer which way the plate is moving because the plate will always appear to be moving towards the older islands as shown here and this is an important concept to remember as you prepare for the quiz now hotspots are those plumes of hot mantle that is rising from the core mantle boundary they don't just occur over oceanic crust though we have them occurring underneath continental crust as well the important thing to remember about hot spots is that they form independent of plate boundaries hot spots underneath continental crust are also the result of a relatively stationary mantle plume except these produce more viscous rhyolitic magma similar to the melting we see at continental rips where we have decompression melting of the mantle below and as it rises and pulls underneath the continent it results in additional heat transfer magma that continues to add silica to the melt forming these ultra viscous rhyolitic magmas and these can result in the most explosive eruptions on earth one example of that is sitting quietly for now underneath yellowstone here you can see the hot spot underneath the north american plate that is currently sitting underneath yellowstone the last eruption was 0.6 million years ago or 600 000 years ago but you can see here that there have been many eruptions and we even believe that the columbia river basalt that we talked about earlier was one explosive or a series of these eruptions underneath the hot spot now just like the pacific plate the north american plate appears to move in the direction where the calderas are aging here's a map of those hot spots again remember hot spots do not occur at plate boundaries they are thought to be caused by those hot mantle plumes and those hot spots remain stationary for long periods of geologic time here i'm just going to show some recent eruptions that were associated with those platonic settings that we've talked about here's mount cinebung in indonesia in an eruption that occurred last year here's picaya erupting in guatemala here's an eruption from last year with mount merapi in indonesia you can see here that it is very prominently cone-shaped because this is a composite volcano sitting over a convergent subduction zone eruptions do not just occur on the ring of fire here's an eruption from last year of mount aetnan italy europe's most active volcano here's an eruption on st vincent in the caribbean last year here's a photo showing lava flows from a volcano on in iceland just last year we even have volcanoes all the way down in antarctica here's mount erebus erupting last year here's kilauea on the big island of hawaii which is probably the world's most active volcano which has been continually erupting for the last 60 years this photo was taken in 2017 but it really looks the same today so hopefully you understand why studying volcanoes are so important over 450 million people worldwide live near active volcanoes which is about nine percent of earth's population many major population centers are located near active or dormant volcanoes attempting to predict volcanic eruptions and evacuating populations is really our only option because we can't stop or prevent the eruptions from happening here's mount rainier mount rainier is only 54 miles away from over half a million people seattle washington here's mexico city which is near two active volcanoes it's only 43 miles from nine million people here's one of those volcanoes erupting in 2015 near mexico city interrupted 30 times in less than 24 hours the mountain's name means smoking mountain aztec and has 15 major eruptions since 1519. here's that eruption just last year mount fuji is only 62 miles from 12 million people in tokyo japan ninety percent of the world's most dangerous volcanoes occur in indonesia the philippines japan mexico and ethiopia in 2020 there were 72 eruptions from 67 different volcanoes and just last year there were 78 eruptions from 74 different volcanoes 30 of them or new eruptions so far this year 47 volcanoes have erupted or have continued erupting and there are about 139 active volcanoes worldwide with about 18 to 20 considered to be currently in a highly active state now these volcanoes come with a whole host of hazards from the primary eruption itself like lava flows and pyroclastic flows which we will talk about both in the next video they also include volcanic bombs nue ardentes which are the incandescent cloud of gas ash and lava fragments ejected from a volcano that looks like glowing ash ash deposits and clouds and even poisonous gas but there are also secondary effects of a volcanic eruption that can be just as hazardous such as mud flows that we call lahars and we will talk about that later debris flows in avalanches floods fires contamination of surface and groundwater and even acid rain and in the next and final two videos of this module we will explore some of these volcanic hazards in more detail

