howdy everyone and welcome to the final video of module 5. in this video we're going to be exploring the rest of the volcanic hazards although as you saw a couple videos ago there are even more than just what we mentioned in this class in this video we're going to be exploring the hazards of ash and tefra landslides lahars and volcanic gases volcanic ash and tephra are significant hazards that can impact communities hundreds even thousands of miles away from a volcano for years after an eruption your textbook talks about the volcanic ash as a hazard to airplanes because jet engines can be damaged when flying through a cloud of volcanic ash a recent example of ash's global impact happened in 2010 this occurred when there was an eruption of one of iceland's volcanoes which i won't even try to pronounce created a thick plume of ash all over europe straining hundreds of thousands of travelers for several weeks ash has also been known to damage car engines as well but probably the worst part of volcanic ash is that it can bury entire landscapes and kill crops making farmland unusable for years even decades after an eruption it is also extremely harmful to breathe in and can not only cause respiratory distress by damaging the lungs but can even cause death ash is very heavy especially when wet and can cause roof collapse ash particles can be ejected high into the atmosphere and block sunlight causing temporary atmosphere cooling a famous example of this occurred in 1815 after the violent eruption of mount timbura in indonesia and this was known as the year without a summer it even caused snowfall on the east coast of the united states in the summer again ash is an extremely significant hazard with global implications for long periods of time here i'm going to show a video of the impact of volcanic ash explosive volcanic eruptions send clouds full of rock and fine grained ash to great heights in the atmosphere ash has spread over large areas by the wind gradually the rocks and ash fall to the ground with the largest material falling closest to the volcano near the vent falling rocks can cause death and injury people caught in a shower of rock should protect their heads and seek refuge indoors that the largest rocks can break through roofs and hot rocks can cause fires people for kilometers to hundreds of kilometers downwind of an eruption are at risk from volcanic ash both during the eruption and when ash is stirred up by the wind or human activities for months or even years later volcanic ash is an irritant to the skin eyes and lungs and can affect breathing children the elderly and those with chronic heart or lung conditions are especially vulnerable and should avoid exposure as it may trigger conditions such as asthma layers of ash can bury land and buildings roofs may collapse under thick layers of ash especially if the ash gets wet the safest option is to evacuate areas near the volcano but if caught seek shelter and sturdy buildings avoiding those with flat roofs agriculture can be impacted through damage and burial of crops and machinery and injury or death of livestock through ingestion of ash and restricted access to clean food and water water supplies and wastewater systems can be disrupted through damage blockage or contamination all forms of transportation may be disrupted a stop during an asphalt and for days afterwards heavy ash falls can reduce visibility and make roads slippery vehicles can break down as engines are clogged with ash airports railways and ports are commonly shut flights may be cancelled because airborne ash can cause catastrophic damage to aircraft scientists and authorities can provide information on what areas will be most affected by volcanic ash fall for those who live near a volcano having an emergency kit will help in the event of an eruption if outdoors or if your indoor environment is ashy wear a face mask designed to block fine particles holding cloth over your nose and mouth will provide limited protection skin should be covered contact lenses removed and eyes protected if advised to evacuate follow all instructions and do not return until advised that it's safe take care when cleaning up ash as deaths and injury due to heart attacks and falls are possible thick deposits can be heavy and ash can easily become airborne making breathing difficult many people live in areas frequently impacted by asphalt preparation and coordinated organized cleanup operations can help you live alongside volcanoes landslides by definition are large masses of wet or dry rock and soil that fall slide or flow under the force of gravity they are common hazards on volcanic cones due to their steep tall slopes volcanic landslides can be triggered by one or more of the following conditions they can be triggered by the intrusion of magma into the volcano the magma releases volcanic gases that can be dissolved in the groundwater creating a hot acidic hydrothermal system that weakens the rock they can also be triggered by an explosive eruption or a large earthquake directly beneath a volcano or nearby heavier long-lived rainfall can also trigger a landslide by saturating the ground not only are landslides deadly by destroying things in their path but they can also trigger an eruption by removing a large part of a volcano in a landslide it can decrease the pressure on the magmatic system below allowing it to explode outwards like we saw happen at mount st helens which i will talk about more later on in this video volcanic landslides especially the collapse of a volcanic cone can trigger tsunami if they occur underwater or travel offshore this happened dramatically in 1883 when the northern half of a volcano on the indonesian island of krakatoa plunged into the sunda strait creating a tsunami that was more than 100 feet in height 36 000 people were killed along the coast of java and sumatra as a result a lahar is a mud flow that occurs on an active or inactive volcano and can be very deadly impacting communities tens of kilometers away they occur when volcanic debris becomes saturated with water and rapidly moves down steep volcanic slopes and they generally follow the path of rivers and streams some lahars are triggered when rising magma gets close to the surface of an ice-covered volcano like we saw with mount saint helens causing large volumes of snow and ice to suddenly melt mixing with ash and debris others happen when heavy rains saturate weathered volcanic deposits this means that lahars can occur even when a volcano is not erupting when mount saint helens erupted several lahars were generated racing down river valleys at speeds of over 20 miles per hour these floods are not just water but more like a slurry of wet cement carrying solid debris that can reach the size of a house in 1985 another deadly lahar was triggered in colombia during the eruption of nevado del rues in the andes mountain the hot pyroclastic material melted the snow and ice and sent a slurry of ash and debris down three major river valleys reaching speeds of 60 miles per hour and killing 25 000 people mount rainier in washington is often considered to be america's most dangerous volcano because like nevada del ruiz it is covered in a thick layer of year-round snow and ice and it has more than a hundred thousand people living in the valleys around it many of these homes are even built on old deposits of these lahars a future eruption or even a period of heavier than usual rainfall might produce lahars here that can be just as destructive here's a figure showing a lahar off of a volcano that is erupting you can see here that the lahars follow the valleys of rivers and streams and they can occur in very very thick amounts covering homes in their entirety a map showing mount rainier you can see all the river valleys along mount rainier contain lots of cities such as electron or team even all the way to tacoma the yellows and reds shown on this map are areas that would be impacted by lahar here's a video that demonstrates the hazards of lahars a little bit better than just reading words on a screen a major danger on many volcanoes comes from floods of water mixed with volcanic debris these floods are called lahars lahars are more destructive than a normal flood because they contain large amounts of rock ash mud and debris boulders swept along by the lahar can sometimes be the size of a car they can form very quickly and flow down the volcano into the surrounding valleys often at high speeds several lahars often occur in quick succession lahars are a major cause of death and volcanic eruptions they can travel great distances many kilometers or even many tens of kilometers so communities far from the volcano can still be in great danger there are many causes of lahars a very common cause is if there's heavy rain an eruption can cover the sides of a volcano with loose rocks and ash vegetation in soil which normally absorbs the rain and prevents floods can be destroyed by the eruption adding to the problem when it rains heavily rot ash and debris are easily swept into the water forming lahars the rocks and debris give the lahar extra destructive energy and often the flows move much faster than someone can run some volcanoes are covered in glass airs in ice or snow eruptions of hot rocks can melt the ice or snow rapidly to form births of huge volumes of water that form lahars lahars can occur at any time during a volcanic eruption but they can also happen many years afterwards fortunately there can be warnings given about lahars if heavy rain is forecast then the chances of allah increases for those places threatened evacuation is the only option if there's not enough time to evacuate then people can protect themselves by immediately leaving valleys and going to high ground hiding in buildings is not safe as large lahars can destroy buildings or flow into them but the upper floors of a strong building may offer some protection if there's no alternative volcanoes can also emit poisonous gases endangering humans and livestock even when they're not actively erupting the most common gas emitted is water vapor and it's not exactly harmful to breathe but it can be released at extremely hot temperatures and can be deadly if you come into contact with it carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide are the most toxic gases released carbon dioxide can be a silent killer because it is odorless and colorless it is denser than air so it does not rise rapidly and can be breathed in without the knowledge of its presence depriving the brain of oxygen a tragic example of this occurred in lake naios in cameroon in 1986. nios is a deep lake along the flanks of a dormant volcano however gases like carbon dioxide from this volcano were still being emitted beneath the lake scientists believe that a landslide into lake niles stirred the lake enough to release a large cloud of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere which suffocated 1746 people and 3 500 livestock in nearby towns and villages here is another video that shows the hazards of volcanic gases the molten rock stored beneath volcanoes called magma contains dissolved gases which are released during eruptions or emitted when the volcanoes quiet escaping through the soil hot springs lakes and gas vents called funerals there are several types of volcanic gas some form a cloud that looks like fog known as vog other times the gases are invisible the most common gas is water vapor or steam steam plumes can often be seen reaching high into the atmosphere above volcanoes there can be substantial amounts of other gases which can sometimes be toxic to people and animals and damage crops and property carbon dioxide is colorless and odourless this means you can't see it or smell it it's heavier than air so it can collect in low-lying areas lakes and confined spaces even short exposure to too much carbon dioxide can cause unconsciousness and death other gases contain sulfur these are colorless but some have a strong smell like rotten eggs sulfurous gases irritate your skin eyes nose and throat the smell can act as a warning but it disappears at high concentrations where it becomes highly toxic causing unconsciousness and death long range hazards can form when gases react with rain water to form acid rain and sunlight in the atmosphere to create particles which can cause health impacts even hundreds of kilometers from the volcano large eruptions can produce such enormous amounts of gas that the world's climate can be affected for years as the gas acts to block out some of the sun's energy persistent plumes of volcanic gas may cause long-term damage to agriculture and to people's health however normally volcanic gases become harmless as they are diluted quickly in the air scientists monitor volcanic gases during and between eruptions monitoring can allow for warnings when gas levels are potentially hazardous mount vesuvius which is a composite volcano found in italy erupted explosively and suddenly in the year 79. for hundreds of years prior to the eruption the volcano laid dormant with people and vineyards flourishing all along its slopes in less than 24 hours however the entire city of pompeii was entombed in ash and pumice scientists believe that during the first day of the eruption that it rained ash and pumice at a rate of five to six inches per hour causing most of the roofs in pompeii to collapse and then suddenly a surge of a pyroclastic flow killed those who had somehow survived the initial ash fall causing their remains to be buried so quickly and preserve their tragic ending for centuries to come now i mentioned mount st helens as an example of many hazards that we've talked about in this module so let's just go into detail exactly what went on in mount st helens and during the eruption in 1980 this figure shows really nicely how the mount st helens evolved leading up to that eruption prior to the eruption the magma chamber was considered empty however over time that magma chamber inflated as the magma rose from below creating a bulge on the side of the mountain that even scientists were monitoring and could see then weakened by an earthquake the north slope slipped this released pressure on the magma chamber causing the dissolved gases to expand and blast out sideways causing the eruption itself here's a photo that was taken a week before that eruption showing that giant bulge on the side of the mountain pretty obvious to see that something was going on beneath this mountain here's a time lapse photograph of the may 18 corruption in 1980 in the top left you can see the mountain is relatively quiet followed beneath that an image showing the landslide where the northern slope of this mountain collapsed and that released pressure that was on the magma chamber allowing the gas and magma to explode outwards that you can see in the remaining photographs a photo showing that mount st helen's eruption you can see here a very large eruptive column with ash being ejected miles into the atmosphere here's a map showing the damage from mount st helen's eruption you can see here that they were lateral blast deposits shown in this purple color or brownish purple color that really covered a huge extensive area surrounding the volcano itself now keep in mind the scale of this map in red this is where we have those pyroclastic flows that we talked about in the last video that impacted large area as well but stayed relatively concentrated closer to the volcano itself but you'll notice the debris avalanches which were the landslide deposits reached much farther away from the volcano and then those mud flow deposits which we call those lahars traveled even further even off of this map completely here's another photo showing mount st helens before the eruption this is looking at its east flank and here's the same view of the volcano after the eruption you can see here that the mountain has been dramatically changed here's a side by side before and after that eruption not just the mountain has been completely changed but the area surrounding the mountain has also been changed you can see here that the mountain has lost a significant portion of its height but if you look at the front of this image you'll notice before the eruption we had vast forests or after the eruption you can see that those trees are no longer there they have been blown over from the blasts and then covered with a thick layer of ash here's a pre-eruption view of spirit lake notice the snow and ice and the vast forests that surround this lake here's a view of spirit lake after the eruption here's a photo showing the fallen timber from 1980 eruption in bouncing helens you can see that trees here in the forest that surrounded the mountain were treated almost like matchsticks and blown over like they were nothing and here's a map showing the ash fallout from mount st helens in red this is where we had the most significant ash fall with thicknesses of up to five centimeters however we had a large portion of the united states that was impacted from this ash fall shown in purple and these areas had up to 1.25 centimeters of ash here's a photo showing some of that ash fallout now we also had lahars we had almost every volcanic hazard that you can imagine with mount saint helens remember our lahars those volcanic mud flows here you can see on the left them the lahars washing out bridges and there on the right is showing you the deposits 20 years later showing that there were huge logs that were carried within this lahar not just water ash and debris but everything that it came into contact with it continued to carry down hill here's a photo showing the impact of the lahar you see white arrows here on the tree trunks that are showing how high the lahar actually got and there's a person circled for scale here's mount st helens 35 years after the eruption this was taken in 2015 and really looks similar today completely changed the landscape surrounding that mountain for decades and decades to come now here in this image you can see what mount st helens looks like today it's peaceful for now but it is still rumbling so what can we do to minimize the impact of these destructive natural processes well volcano monitoring is critical especially for the millions of people who live near one there are three main ways we can monitor volcanoes and infer that an eruption may be likely in the near future scientists study changes in patterns of earthquakes and in general we see a sharp increase in seismic activity followed by a period of quiet and this has been shown to be a predictor of many volcanic eruptions but not always scientists also monitor the volcanic cone for inflation or deflation by using remote sensing devices just like we saw with mount st helens as a magma chamber begins to fill up it can expand and inflate the volcano prior to an eruption and thirdly scientists also monitor the changes in the amount and the composition of gases released by the volcano this monitoring has revealed that some volcanoes show an increase in sulfur dioxide leading up to an eruption of course even with all this monitoring in place a volcano can still erupt with little to no warning and residents who live near one should have a plan in the event of an unexpected eruption this concludes module 5. you should now have all the information you need to complete the participation activity i highly recommend that you review this chapter in your textbook prior to taking the quiz but as always please reach out to me if you have any questions this also concludes the modules that will be included in your first exam modules 1 2 3 four and this module five will all be included in your exam i highly recommend that you review the participation activity questions and the quizzes for all five modules prior to taking your exam but as always please never hesitate to reach out if you need any further assistance

